<TEXT>
a fragmented 20milelong fuel slick 
drifted wednesday past steel plants and boat marinas on the ohio 
river into ohio and west virginia where officials said it posed 
less of a threat to drinking water 
it does appear to be dissipating said dave plank chief of 
technical services for the pennsylvania department of environmental 
resources as the oil moves down the river it will pose less of 
a risk 
the slicks leading edge moving about 1 mph was near east 
liverpool ohio on wednesday afternoon said department 
spokeswoman betsy mallison 
at least 75000 gallons of diesel fuel gasoline and kerosene 
poured from a severed interstate pipeline into an allegheny river 
tributary friday following a mudslide near freeport 35 miles 
northeast of pittsburgh the allegheny flows into the ohio river at 
pittsburgh 
earlier this week the spill threatened the water supplies of as 
many as 1 million people along the allegheny and ohio rivers 
early wednesday it passed the beaver county community of 
midland five miles east of the ohiowest virginia line 
the midland water authority which serves 11700 residents in 
midland ohioville and industry reopened its filter plants intake 
valves at 2 pm at about half normal pumping volume said chief 
operator dan zuppe the valves were opened after state 
environmental officials tested the water for oil 
the spill has pretty much passed us by zuppe said wednesday 
evening were under the direction of the der and they will give 
us the direction when to go back on full 
weirton about 65 river miles south of pittsburgh was the first 
west virginia town whose water supply was threatened by the spill 
ken capozzoli a maintenance operator at the weirton water 
treatment plant said the authority would close its intakes and 
rely on well water until the spill passed 
we dont really know how long the wells can supply us but 
well do fine for the couple of days it should take for the spill 
to pass he said 
at east liverpool the first ohio community on the river south 
of the spill two intake valves near the rivers surface were 
closed as a precaution said glenn woodward water superintendent 
for the city of 7000 residents 
intakes deeper in the river continued to draw water wednesday 
afternoon because no oil had been detected that deep according to 
woodward 
we are anticipating it could hit anytime he said 
in midland a voluntary water conservation measure was in effect 
the spill was no threat to other water systems serving beaver 
county because they depend on well water said county emergency 
management agency director russell chiodo 
several manufacturing plants including a steel plant in 
midland a tin mill in aliquippa and the beaver valley i and ii 
nuclear power plants continued drawing water directly from the 
ohio for industrial use chiodo said 
in pittsburgh where small traces of petroleum were detected in 
river water mayor sophie masloff lifted her call for water 
conservation and water authorities along the allegheny river that 
had been affected by the spill were back in operation 
water conservation measures in some of those communities 
however remained in effect 
in harrison township the only community where the taps ran dry 
about 20000 residents were told to boil water to kill bacteria 
that might have grown in the system when it was empty 
</TEXT>
