<TEXT>
the nations roman catholic bishops on thursday 
announced that they have hired a major public relations firm and a 
polling concern for a nationwide campaign to persuade catholics and 
noncatholics to oppose abortion 
the bishops are expected to spend as much as 5 million over 
three to five years on the effort the new york times said in 
friday editions 
given the stakes life itself we can do no less said 
cardinal john oconnor archbishop of new york who made the 
announcement as chairman of the bishops committee for prolife 
activities 
the firms chosen hill amp knowlton and the wirthlin group 
represent two of the nations best known and most influential 
political and lobbying strategists 
the wirthlin group is a leading republican polling operation 
that served ronald reagan during his campaign for and time in the 
white house 
john berard deputy general manager of hill amp knowltons 
washington office said the campaign would involve neither lobbying 
nor electoral politics he said it was unclear whether it would 
include advertising 
we are focusing our efforts on a broadbased public education 
and information campaign to make the bishops better heard on 
abortion he said 
oconnor said in his statement we want this effort to unfold 
on peaceful grounds without vitriol as we work to encourage both 
within and beyond our faith community serious considerations of 
moral ends means and achievable policy goals 
the catholic bishops have hired media consultants for events 
like pope john paul iis visit to the united states in 1987 but 
never before on the abortion issue 
oconnor said money for the campaign would be raised from 
private individuals or organizations and would not detract from 
existing programs 
</TEXT>
