<TEXT>
researchers today reported an advance toward 
finding the defective gene or genes responsible for spinal muscular 
atrophy a disabling and sometimes lethal disease of children 
they narrowed down the search to a particular part of one 
chromosome one of the 23 pairs of threadlike structures on which 
genes reside 
finding the gene or genes responsible for the disease may give 
clues for developing treatments researchers said 
no firm numbers exist on how many people have the disease which 
weakens muscles by attacking nerves that control voluntary muscles 
the study included three forms of the disease that strike a total 
of about one in 10000 newborns said study coauthor t conrad 
gilliam 
the acute form the most common appears at birth or in infancy 
and usually kills by age 4 two chronic forms usually appear in 
early childhood with effects ranging from relatively mild muscle 
weakness to profound weakness and death in early adolescence 
ashley antolak the 6yearold national poster child for the 
muscular dystrophy association has a chronic form of spinal 
muscular atrophy 
the new study found evidence that a defective gene or genes 
causing the chronic forms is on chromosome number 5 it also 
suggests that the acute form may come from the same source or a 
nearby gene said study coauthor linda brzustowicz 
brzustowicz gilliam and others at columbia university and the 
new york state psychiatric institute did the work with theodore 
munsat of tufts university and the new england medical center in 
boston and others at the university of utah medical center in salt 
lake city odyssey biomedical corp in west paterson nj and 
scientists in britain west germany and poland 
the work is reported in todays issue of the british journal 
nature 
it marks a very important first step toward developing 
treatments and preventing the disease through prenatal diagnosis 
and detection of people at risk for having affected children 
genetics expert robert williamson of london university in england 
commented wednesday 
</TEXT>
