<TEXT>
never mind the trifling banter or the continual 
references to the buckets of sweat that cascaded down her ample 
frame 
none of that mattered when sarah vaughan seized the stage and 
seduced a willing audience with the moody excitement of her jazz 
stylings 
it was always sweet surrender 
she caressed a song with all the colorings of her voice 
sometimes teasing with the weighty depths of low d sometimes more 
direct with her pure c sometimes playful with inspired scat 
sometimes sentimental with soft singing from her soul 
who could resist such a temptress 
for those who knew and worked with sarah vaughan who died 
tuesday night at age 66 few could 
i traveled around the world with her and shed be sold out 
and people wouldnt even understand the language she was singing 
in recalled drummer harold jones who worked with vaughan for a 
decade and had been friends with the song stylist for 25 years 
sometimes id go up to them later and ask them why they came 
to the concert if they couldnt understand her why they thought 
she was so great they would say it was the feeling the feeling 
of the way she sang thats how they knew she was great 
she sang of love and life easy breezy tunes such as east of 
the sun moody bluesy ballads like easy living and the man 
i love complicated jazz songs that ended in rollicking scat 
fascinatin rhythm i remember april 
and along the way she always had fun 
once at a carnegie hall concert in 1980 she performed duke 
ellingtons sophisticated lady and confessed to a startled 
audience that she didnt know the lyrics so shed have to refer to 
the sheet music 
ive never done it until now she said with a laugh this 
could be my first and last time its not an easy song to sing if 
you hear me falter help 
she didnt she never did or if she did no one noticed or no 
one cared 
she was always an absolute nervous wreck before performing 
recalled andy simkins vaughans bassist theres a certain edge 
you need to perform but she would be a wreck she was fine after 
she went on stage or after she started the first set at a club 
she was always a little girl i always thought of her as a 
little sister there was a certain naivete and then again she was 
old professional show business and had stories for days billy 
eckstine was really her mentor when she was depressed and nobody 
could get to her shed call for b he was the only one who could 
get to her 
vaughan worked with eckstine in his own band after they both 
left earl hines in 1944 together they ignited romance with lovely 
duets on jazz standards alone they both produced a litany of hit 
romantic records 
she and eckstine reunited a few years back at the kool jazz 
festival in new york and reprised some of those love ballads but 
time had robbed them of memory and both whipped out their glasses 
to glance at an occasional lyric for passing strangers a song 
popular in england in the 1940s 
they had known each other so long they didnt even have to 
rehearse said jazz producer george wein it was the warmth of 
love that those two had for each other so the lyrics didnt mean 
anything it was the music 
as a soloist vaughan eventually ran into george shearing then a 
young jazz pianist who had emigrated to the united states from 
britain in 1947 she was the first vocalist with whom he worked 
jimmy jones the pianist had a trick whereby he would stab at 
a chord and then hit the sustaining pedal before the vibrations 
were gone and instead of getting baahhh hed get bink shearing 
recalled in an interview it was a wonderful trick and he and 
sarah would do that to tenderly he did that prior to the last 
note and then shed do some vocals that were just incredible 
she could hold on to great big long notes without vibrato 
vaughan took that great gift and used it for popular music when 
she recorded brokenhearted melody in 1958 and later with such 
middleoftheroad tunes as send in the clowns the switch 
generated new converts for her but saddened jazz purists 
i dont really feel she switched over said harold jones 
she went in and did them and then back on the gig she was still 
singing lush life and tenderly 
simkins wasnt bothered with pop sidesteps either i learned a 
lot from her he said she probably taught me how to play a 
ballad on my instrument she was always my image as to how a 
love song or ballad should be played 
vaughan never thought of herself as a pop singer or a jazz 
singer or even a great singer and as popular as she was jones 
said she never thought of herself as having a hit song 
to me she was the greatest simkins said what i loved 
was she never thought of herself as sarah vaughan and her trio she 
always thought of herself as a quartet 
a powerful and pleasing instrument that gave pleasure to 
generations 
</TEXT>
