<TEXT>
undaunted by shortages in money and name 
recognition four eager north carolina democrats are jockeying for 
a shot at toppling conservative republican sen jesse helms in 
november 
with the primary election just a month away voters so far have 
been spared the roughandtumble politicking that early on 
characterized the 1984 race between helms and his democratic 
challenger thengov jim hunt 
this time around all four democratic challengers have been 
campaigning across the state to expand their appeal but none has 
broken out of his regional base and into the lead 
none of the democratic candidates have the widespread name 
recognition of a jim hunt but as we get closer to the primary i 
think that will resolve itself said state democratic party 
chairman lawrence davis 
its been an incredibly different campaign from 1984 said 
carter wrenn of the national congressional club helms political 
organization 
in that year neither helms nor hunt had a serious primary 
challenger so both candidates began gunning for one another early 
spending a national record 26 million on a race marked by negative 
campaigning and personal slurs 
the main challengers in this years may 8 democratic primary are 
former charlotte mayor harvey gantt who is seeking to become 
the first black to win a statewide race in north carolina gantts 
supporters say a solid black vote combined with his proven ability 
to attract white voters in his mayoral races could help him garner 
40 percent of the democratic vote and avoid a runoff 
southport prosecutor mike easley who has developed a 
reputation as a drug fighter in a region whose coastal areas have 
been used by smugglers since pirate days easley has the support of 
many party activists who were involved in hunts campaigns and has 
campaigned on themes such as day care and the environment that are 
likely to attract baby boomers 
rp bo thomas a produce broker who served nine years in 
the state senate thomas has campaigned on a strong populist 
message that he says can win back jessecrats conservative 
white democrats who routinely vote for helms 
former insurance commissioner john ingram whose major campaign 
theme has been a plan to force insurance companies to finance a 
highrisk pool to make affordable health insurance available to 
almost everyone 
early polls show helms ahead of all four potential challengers 
a reversal from 1984 when similar surveys had hunt in the lead by 
the november election however helms had hacked away at hunts 
support to take 52 percent of the vote 
helms 43 percent approval rating also is higher now than in 
1984 wrenn said 
while the noise of the campaign hasnt been as loud as in 1984 
both sides say the equation for victory remains the same helms 
starts out with 40 to 45 percent of the vote and his eventual 
democratic opponent can count on roughly the same amount 
you have people who are yellowdog democrats who will always 
vote against helms because hes a republican said thad beyle a 
political science professor at the university of north carolina at 
chapel hill and then there are others who will always vote 
against helms because of his views 
wrenn said the outcome depends on the 10 percent to 20 percent 
of the electorate identified as swing voters most of whom are 
registered as democrats 
they have to get all of their votes and a third of ours to 
win democratic chairman davis said of the republicans thats 
the same equation weve had for the last several years 
beyle said helms tactic for reaching those voters judging from 
his last campaign is he gets hold of some issue well before the 
campaign and beats it to death 
in 1984 it was the martin luther king holiday bill beyle 
said in 1990 its the national endowment for the arts which 
helms has criticized for supporting art he considers obscene 
wrenn attributes helms strength in the early polls to two 
factors one were not running against jim hunt a very popular 
governor and two all the democratic candidates positions are 
left of center and pretty extremely left of center 
beyle said helms may be starting out stronger this time because 
he is not yet facing an identified opponent right now hes 
running against x candidate beyle said 
