this is not a great age of correspondence says 
the recently retired editor of the times venerable letters column 
though the mailbags still bulge with opinions both profound and 
eccentric 
there are many people who simply do not know how to put words 
onto paper they have to become so used to talking on the telephone 
or dictating into machines and having them tidied up by their 
secretaries leon pilpel said in an interview published in 
wednesdays editions of the times 
of the 300 letters a day only about 8 percent are 
publishable i am not talking about matters of syntax but about 
importance or meetness 
many of them are pretty mundane although frequently half a 
dozen not very brilliant ones can be made into a very good 
correspondence indeed with a bit of judicious editing and the 
specific approval of the letterwriter 
