<TEXT>
putting out a newspaper without promotion is 
like winking at a girl in the dark wellintentioned but 
ineffective said press mogul william randolph hearst 
his quotation adorns an exhibit the american journalist 
paradox of the press it opens today at the library of congress 
and winks in full selfconsciousness at the american press in 
every manifestation from feisty hearst to feisty benjamin harris 
americas first newsman 
harris published the first american newspaper on sept 25 1690 
it lasted one issue before it was closed down by the british 
authorities the sole surviving copy was flown back from london for 
the exhibit 
the show underwritten by a 325000 grant from the gannett 
foundation and running through aug 12 coincides with the 67th 
annual meeting of the american society of newspaper editors whose 
members gathered at the library wednesday night to celebrate the 
occasion 
on display behind glass the little bedside notebook in which 
washington post reporter bob woodward made notes when the city desk 
awakened him on saturday june 17 1972 to tell him to cover a 
breakin at the watergate hotel 
he scratched down 5 men arrested at demo nat headquarters 
wsoph photo equip 
joined by street reporter carl bernstein he went on to uncover 
the watergate scandal that led to the resignation of richard m 
nixon as president two years later 
nothing so dramatic appeared in public occurrences both 
forreign and domestick benjamin harris scrawny paper three 
printed pages and a blank one it reported a suicide by hanging 
the spread of a smallpox epidemic and rumors about improprieties by 
the king of france 
harris proposed to publish once a month or if any glut of 
occurrences happen oftener but the authorities concluded that 
his paper contained sundry doubtful and uncertain reports and 
closed it down 
the paradox of the press is what the exhibit explores what 
curator david halaas says has been the lovehate relationship 
between the people and the news gatherers 
on one hand members of the press are seen as truthseekers and 
watchdogs of government on the other hand theyre seen as 
gossipmongers and purveyors of slander he said 
on exhibit are war correspondent ernie pyles typewriter the 
clippings in abraham lincolns pockets when he was assassinated 
the hustling newsboys who learned to condense a news story into a 
few catchy words the zany cartoons of rube goldberg such as one 
entitled simple way to light a cigar in an automobile traveling 
50 miles an hour a battlefield picture of a grinning boyish 
helmeted war cartoonist bill mauldin and the cluttered rolltop 
desk of william allen white editorowner of kansas emporia 
gazette who came to epitomize the courageous commonsense small 
town editor 
and too a poster advertising the new york sunday tribune the 
picture showed conductors tossing bundles of papers from a moving 
train onto a suburban platform the legend it has an illustrated 
supplement and being a high class dignified paper of superb 
merit is especially worthy to be read by intelligent and honest 
people 
back at the asne meeting another paradox of the press was the 
topic of a speech given by retiring association president loren 
ghiglione he told colleagues that journalists have become so 
successful comfortable wellpaid and suburban that they have 
forfeited their role as fighters for societys underdogs 
we often think of ourselves as davids fighting the 
establishment but the public sees us more and more as statusquo 
establishment goliaths said ghiglione publisher and editor of 
the southbridge mass news 
while we say we comfort the afflicted and afflict the 
comfortable we need to guard against looking at the world 
increasingly through the eyes of the comfortable he said 
