<TEXT>
latin american cocaine barons 
stymied by washingtons war on drugs are relying more and more on 
european ports to get their merchandise to us streets police say 
moreover officials say all across europe police seizures of 
cocaine have at least doubled in the past few years and the drug is 
challenging heroin as the narcotic of choice on the continent 
last month the national police intelligence service published 
figures that show cocaine seizures in the netherlands to have risen 
dramatically over the past three years 
dutch police confiscated 7700 pounds of cocaine in the first 
three months of this year alone more than double the 3120 pounds 
seized in all of last year and almost three times the 1130 pounds 
in 1988 
commissioner peter broeders of the intelligence services crime 
information division said drug kingpins from colombia and other 
latin american countries are searching for routes that are less 
vulnerable than the direct routes to the united states 
broeders in a radio interview tuesday upon his return from a 
twoweek trip visiting drug enforcement agencies in the united 
states attributed the shift to president bushs 79 billion war 
on drugs 
the tough way in which americans are handling the drug trade 
from south america is forcing the drug barons to shift their supply 
lines and theyre doing it through europe broeders said 
crime information division spokesman peter de waard said in an 
interview wednesday that another factor in the growing drug 
seizures is that the north american market is so saturated latin 
american drug barons cant sell there any more 
instead they are turning to europe he said 
on feb 28 police in the dutch north sea port of ijmuiden 
seized 6600 pounds of cocaine concealed in a shipment of frozen 
fruit juice although the cocaines origin remains unclear police 
said four of the eight suspects they arrested claimed to be 
colombian nationals 
broeders said much of the cocaine smuggled into this country is 
believed to be going through rotterdam packed mostly in freight 
containers 
rotterdam is the biggest port in the world and broeders said it 
is physically impossible to open and inspect all of the 25 million 
containers shipped through the port every year 
police seizures of cocaine across europe reached 15435 pounds 
in 1989 
french police hauled in 2000 pounds in 1989 up 58 percent from 
the previous year less than 220 pounds were seized in that country 
in 1982 
in great britain seizures more than quadrupled between 1986 and 
1989 with police confiscating 935 pounds last year 
although heroin seems to be europes most widely used drug 
cocaine is taking over 
1987 was the last year that dutch police hauled in more heroin 
than cocaine de waard said 
both drugs are relatively easy to obtain in the netherlands 
which rarely prosecutes drug abusers but concentrates on capturing 
traffickers 
drugrelated crime is increasing dramatically in holland we 
are seeing more shootouts between drug gangs de waard said 
until recently drug turf battles were relatively rare in the 
netherlands which also has experienced almost none of the violent 
crime associated with crack the highly addictive cocaine 
derivative 
