<TEXT>
pan american world airways security at 
frankfurt airport in west germany remained dangerously flawed for 
more than eight months after the bombing of flight 103 federal 
aviation officials say 
all passengers flying out of frankfurt by pan am are at great 
risk said a june 1989 internal federal aviation administration 
memo read wednesday at a hearing by the presidential commission on 
aviation security and terrorism 
investigators believe terrorists smuggled a bomb in baggage 
aboard flight 103 in frankfurt before the flight switched planes in 
london and blew up over lockerbie scotland killing all 259 people 
aboard and 11 on the ground 
the sevenmember commission which has been looking into the 
dec 21 1988 bombing will send president bush recommendations 
next month for avoiding future aviation terrorist attacks and 
improving government response if they occur 
top federal aviation officials testified wednesday that the 
frankfurt airport is now a model station but they acknowledged 
that serious security problems persisted there until a team of 
airline and faa officials flew to the airport last september and 
corrected the flaws 
commission chairwoman ann mclaughlin sharply criticized the faa 
for allowing the problems with pan am at frankfurt to go 
uncorrected for so long 
ive never seen anything like this in my life ms 
mclaughlin told faa administrator james busey busey who took 
office last july said part of the problem was that his agency was 
leaderless for part of the time after the bombing 
ms mclaughlin said that was an absolutely unacceptable 
excuse for failures at the airport the faa is responsible for 
overseeing security of us airlines in the united states and 
abroad 
pan am chairman thomas plaskett told the commission that the 
airline followed inspection procedures approved by the faa the 
airline is contesting 630000 in fines levied by the agency last 
september for security lapses related to flight 103 and five other 
european flights around the same time 
alleged pan am security lapses in 1989 have not been the subject 
of faa fines however 
faa associate administrator monte belger and security chief ray 
salazar testified that security problems were found at frankfurt 
during inspections in january may june and august 1989 
if i was frustrated in june i hit the ceiling in august 
said belger who received reports of the frankfurt inspections 
he said problems included failure to properly check personnel 
who serviced pan am planes at the airport failure to secure planes 
overnight and problems with ground personnel at the airport 
salazar denied sworn statements by pan am officials that he gave 
them permission before december 1988 to xray checked luggage as an 
alternative to requirements that it be matched to passengers at 
frankfurt 
salazar said that procedure was a violation of faa rules 
although pan am was never fined for it he said faa lawyers advised 
against including the charge when fines were levied 
paul hudson head of one of two organizations formed by 
relatives of flight 103 victims said the faa and pan am 
disclosures at wednesdays hearing confirmed family members 
deepest concerns about airline security 
my daughter had no chance at all hudson said in an 
interview outside the hearing room after pan ams plaskett 
testified that luggage at frankfurt was not handsearched and that 
no special procedures were used following threats against pan am 
flights to the united states 
