<TEXT>
sarah vaughan was remembered by the music 
industry and friends as a singers singer whose powerful range and 
mastery of scatstyle jazz earned her acclaim as the divine one 
or simply sassy 
vaughan died of lung cancer tuesday night at her home in the 
hidden hills area of the san fernando valley she was 66 
sarah vaughan was a complete vocalist and musician frank 
sinatra said wednesday she was an instrument and she had an 
incredible sense of humor put those attributes together and were 
talking about one of the finest vocalists in the history of pop 
music 
some of her most memorable songs were brokenhearted melody 
send in the clowns misty and if you could see me now 
now that shes gone theres no one to measure great singers 
with said entertainer and jazz buff bill cosby 
sarah was like a sister to me and i loved her very much 
said sammy davis jr who is convalescing at his beverly hills home 
from a recurrence of throat cancer 
mayor tom bradley ordered flags at all city buildings lowered to 
halfstaff through friday the last time flags were lowered for the 
death of a celebrity was a year ago when lucille ball died 
a moment of silence was observed wednesday at the apollo theater 
in new yorks harlem where vaughan was discovered a halfcentury 
ago 
vaughans style was formed by her early association with bebop 
she sang with billy eckstine charlie parker and dizzy gillespie in 
the earl hines and eckstine bands in the 1940s 
there will never be another one like sarah vaughan 
gillespie said wednesday 
her nicknames were the divine one the divine sarah and 
sassy often after she introduced the musicians accompanying 
her she coyly introduced herself as della reese 
her deep sultry voice and dramatic colorings distinguished her 
as the finest jazz singer of the 40s 
sarah vaughan was among the most powerful influential and 
soulful voices of all time a perfectionist with an astonishing 
vocal range and a genius for conveying emotion through her music 
said quincy jones who first worked with vaughan in 1957 as the 
arranger on misty 
vocally she was a giant singer said mel torme had sarah 
decided to go another way she would have been a great legit singer 
she could have done opera for instance 
colleagues also praised vaughans mastery of scat singing 
improvising swinging and phrasing but she never thought of 
herself as a specialist 
why do they always call me a jazz singer im just a singer 
sarah would always say said her manager and friend harold levy 
she was a singers singer the greatest 
pianist george shearing who worked with vaughan in the late 
1940s said she was the first vocalist he performed with after 
emigrating to the united states from great britain 
shes going to be very much missed in terms of being the 
exemplary voice in the pop field she was the best contralto in 
pop he said she would hold on to great big long notes 
without vibrato 
born in newark nj vaughan studied piano from age 7 and was a 
church choir member and organist by 12 her father a carpenter 
played guitar and her mother sang in the choir 
in 1942 she accepted a dare trumpetertrombonist jabbo smith 
claimed it was his idea and sang body and soul at an apollo 
theater amateur contest 
i put her on and ill tell you she was absolutely 
astounding the apollos ralph cooper said wednesday she was 
the most unusual thing to take the stage at the apollo 
she made her debut with the hines band at the apollo in 1943 
went with eckstine a year later when he formed his own band then 
sang with john kirbys group by 1946 she had established herself 
as a solo artist 
vaughan won esquires new star award in 1947 and the down beat 
poll as best female jazz vocalist from 1947 through 1952 she won a 
grammy for best female vocal jazz performance for gershwin 
live in 1982 
other songs she recorded included youre blase i cover 
the waterfront body and soul tenderly everything i 
have is yours ill remember april easy living i 
remember clifford heres that rainy day and dont blame 
me she recorded lover man in 1945 with gillespie and parker 
and perdido with count basies band 
her first husband was trumpeter george treadwell she also was 
married to professional football player clyde atkins las vegas 
restaurateur marshall fisher and trumpeter waymon reed 
vaughan is survived by her 87yearold mother ada and her 
daughter actress paris vaughan funeral arrangements were 
incomplete 
</TEXT>
