<TEXT>
creeping like a fiery dragon lava from 
kilauea volcano vaporized two houses and oozed toward four others 
in a rural subdivision on hawaii island 
loren lewisohn watched helplessly wednesday as the lava advanced 
and ignited the house he had built in the kalapana gardens 
subdivision 
if the lava takes away the house nothing can take away the 
experience of building it said lewisohn whose insurance made it 
easier to be philosophical im gaining a lot of respect for the 
awesome force of nature 
lava crept around a support pillar and set fire to the 
latticework an hour later all that was left of lewisohns house 
were the twisted remains of its corrugated metal roof earlier a 
house owned by john and ruth duff erupted in flames after the 
molten rock surged beneath the raised structure 
kilauea volcano has wiped out 78 residences since it began 
erupting more than seven years ago the wooden houses incinerated 
wednesday were the first kalapanaarea homes destroyed by lava 
since december 1986 
residents of 59 homes have been ordered to evacuate civil 
defense officials said all residents of the 125home coastal 
community should be ready to pack their belongings within 72 hours 
the flow had entered the community on tuesday from the west 
passing within several feet of two homes those homes remained 
standing wednesday when the lava flowed into a gulley and toward 
the duff home 
ed torrison whose house was just 20 feet from molten rock that 
was filling his back yard expected to be next 
its a shame to watch this sort of thing happen but its kind 
of exciting too he said 
torrison said he was going to watch the flow from his balcony 
until the last possible minute and take pictures as his home 
burned ive got 12 shots left he said 
the flow on the west side of the subdivision had split into two 
fingers tuesday night before merging wednesday to move down a 
street along the subdivisons western edge 
its just finding low spots said reggie okamura a 
geologist with the hawaiian volcano observatory its like water 
it will seek the quickest route downhill 
okamura said the flow probably would meander in the subdivision 
because it is a relatively level area kim said the flow had no 
direct path toward the ocean without cutting through populated 
areas 
