<TEXT>
peruvians vote sunday for the next president 
of their violencetorn inflationwracked nation opinion polls say 
their choice will be mario vargas llosa one of the worlds most 
celebrated novelists 
apparently the only question is whether vargas llosa 54 will 
fall short of a majority that would force him into a runoff 
against one of the eight other candidates trailing far behind him 
in opinion polls 
regardless of whether a second round is necessary most 
pollsters predict the novelist will be writing the next five years 
of peruvian history as successor to populist president alan garcia 
vargas llosa addressed at least 50000 screaming supporters in 
front of limas palace of justice on wednesday night promising to 
do away with inflation and bring peace to the country 
he said he would make peru again a country of high culture and 
civilization 
the latest published surveys show vargas llosa candidate of the 
centerright democratic front coalition with support of around 45 
percent more than twice that of his nearest competitor luis alva 
castro of the leftofcenter governing aprista party 
the constitution requires a runoff between the top two 
votegetters if no candidate gets more than 50 percent 
nearly 10 million people are registered to vote voting is 
obligatory and violators face stiff penalties including fines 
equivalent to nearly half the minimum wage of 45 a month 
in addition to voting for president and two vice presidents 
peruvians will fill all of the senates 60 seats and congress 180 
seats 
but violence has marred the campaign and threatens to overshadow 
the election guerrillas of the maoistinspired shining path have 
mounted a bombing and assassination campaign to try to thwart it 
and say they will launch electionday armed strikes 
more than 18000 people have been killed as a result of the 
10yearold insurgency the governnment says half the country is 
under emergency rule because of the leftist rebels 
vargas llosa entered politics reluctantly in 1987 after leading 
a huge public rally against garcias plan to nationalize perus 
banks he advocates freemarket policies and foreign investment 
and promises to apply economic shock treatment to perus ravaged 
economy 
backed by a wellheeled publicity campaign vargas llosa enjoyed 
55 percent support as recently as midfebruary but his lead has 
slipped largely due to late surges by alva castro and independent 
candidate alberto fujimori 
fujimori former rector of the national university of 
agriculture was virtually unknown until two months ago pollsters 
say his appeal stems from voters mistrust of professional 
politicians 
people planning to vote for fujimori say they distrust the 
traditional conservative parties supporting vargas llosa a 
political independent 
alva castro 48 became finance minister when garcia was elected 
in 1985 he stuck with garcia through the glory years of 19851987 
when peru had the fastestgrowing economy in south america 
but the freespending policies that paid for the boom also 
brought the bust alva castro quit say critics when he realized 
the economy was running out of steam 
last year peru suffered nearly 3000 percent inflation in the 
last two years the economy has shrunk by 20 percent 
the decline in my partys government weighs on the campaign 
alva castro admitted recently but he promised to correct the 
errors that have been committed 
alva castros campaign has benefitted from an eleventhhour 
spending spree by the garcia government which has used up much of 
the treasurys remaining reserves to subsidize basic services and 
hold down inflation 
many believe the 40yearold garcia wants to position himself 
for the 1995 race and is trying to boost his image before he goes 
out he is prohibited by the constitution from seeking a 
consecutive term 
if necessary a runoff would probably be held in early june the 
exact date depends on how soon results are known from the first 
round 
ballots trickled in for weeks following the 1985 election due to 
poor communications with much of the countrys interior official 
results were not released for nearly two months 
a major concern for the democratic front coalition is whether it 
can win a majority in the congress without it vargas llosa will 
have difficulty imposing the economic austeriy measures he says are 
necessary 
the latest surveys show 10 percent of voters remain undecided 
and the candidates have been campaigning hard to win those votes in 
the final days 
one day recently vargas llosa campaigned in a lima slum 
addressed two rallies in different cities in the andes then flew 
to trujillo 350 miles up the coast 
owing to constant threats by leftist guerrillas the candidates 
often appear with little advance notice flying in and out of 
provincial towns quickly so the rebels cant plan an attack 
the tactic often leaves voters equally surprised 
they come and they go said shopkeeper rosa casa during a 
recent vargas llosa rally in chincha 125 miles southeast of lima 
theyve all been here but chincha still doesnt have water 
chincha still doesnt have electricity nothings going to 
change said ms casa 
she said she had not decided which candidate would get her vote 
</TEXT>
