edward carlson who worked his way from bellhop 
to the chairman of hotel and airline chain ual inc has died of 
cancer at age 78 
carlson who died tuesday night in a seattle hospital was among 
seattles bestknown civic boosters and was credited with the idea 
for the citys trademark space needle built for the 1962 worlds 
fair the idea came from a revolving hotel carlson saw in 
stuttgart west germany 
he joined ual inc in august 1970 when united airlines merged 
with western international hotels now westin hotels carlson had 
headed the hotel chain since 1960 
he retired as uals chief executive officer in 1979 and as 
chairman in 1982 he retired altogether in 1983 after a year as 
chairman of the executive committee of ual 
carlson was born in tacoma on june 4 1911 and moved with his 
divorced mother and sister to seattle after completing grade school 
he entered the hotel business in 1928 working parttime as a 
bellhop at the benjamin franklin hotel in seattle while studying at 
the university of washington 
in 1946 he became the assistant to the president of western 
hotels then a regional hotel chain based in seattle 
