<TEXT>
the government said today that it would 
introduce legislation to outlaw capital punishment which has not 
been carried out in ireland since 1954 
abolishing the death penalty was an element of a coalition deal 
between the fianna fail party and the small progressive democrats 
party that allowed prime minister charles haughey to form a 
government after elections last summer 
current irish law provides for the death sentence for treason 
and for the murder of a member of the government a diplomat a 
foreign head of state or a police or prison officer on duty 
the proposed legislation would prescribe a mandatory sentence of 
40 years for those offenses with a possibility of release after 26 
years and eight months attempted murder of a policeman or prison 
officer would carry a mandatory sentence of 20 years 
the bill published today will be introduced in parliament when 
it reconvenes april 25 it is expected to pass overwhelmingly 
the government is satisfied that the death penalty should now 
be finally removed from the statute book and be replaced for 
treason and capital murder by a realistic custodial penalty which 
will reflect the particularly heinous and serious nature of these 
offences and act as a deterrent said justice minister ray burke 
the last person executed in ireland was michael manning who was 
hanged for the murder of a 65yearold woman 
twelve policemen have been murdered on duty since 1970 although 
some convicts in those cases were sentenced to death their 
sentences were commuted to 40 years in prison 
