the state has agreed to change its policy on 
foster children placement to settle a lawsuit filed by a homosexual 
couple who contended that the policy was discriminatory 
the new policy proposal makes parenting experience not marital 
status the key factor in placement decisions state human servics 
secretary philip johnston said wednesday 
this agreement is a victory for children because it will 
serve their best interests johnston said 
the lawsuit was filed in suffolk superior court in 1986 by 
donald babets and david jean a homosexual couple from boston who 
had two young brothers taken away by state officials 
the men claimed the states policy irrationally and arbitrarily 
presumed that a traditional family setting of a husband and wife 
was the best placement for every foster child 
the policy change makes parenting experience the key factor in 
placement decisions it also says sexual orientation marital 
status race sex religion economic status education and ethnic 
background can all be weighed in a social workers decision 
the policy will continue to encourage social workers to look 
first to placing a child with relatives about 23 percent of the 
8455 children placed in foster care are currently placed with 
relatives 
anthony doniger an attorney who represented babets and jean 
through the civil liberties union of massachusetts said he was 
pleased 
the changes that the government has agreed to make in this 
policy now returns the system to what it was before this whole 
controversy was created he said 
the policy under dispute called for trying to place foster 
children in a traditional setting of a married couple with 
parenting experience couples without parenting experience or a 
single person with experience were given second priority the third 
and final group included individuals without parenting experience 
