gov richard celeste needs time to study the bill but he 
certainly believes in getting drinking drivers off the road his 
press secretary heidi findley said wednesday 
the senate passed the bill 320 on wednesday a few minutes 
after the house approved it 879 
drivers who refuse to take a bloodalcohol test or those with 
previous drunken driving convictions who register more than 10 on 
alcohol tests can have their licenses confiscated by arresting 
officers 
i think we truly have the most innovative law in our 
country said rep marc guthrie the bills house sponsor he 
said it will help curb traffic deaths last year more than 500 
people were killed in traffic accidents in ohio and 8000 were 
injured 
the bill requires a license suspension of at least 90 days for a 
first offense and increases in steps that range up to three years 
for a fourth offense 
it provides that judges may not grant driving privileges for 
workers for at least 15 days on a first offense 30 days on a 
second and 180 days for a third 
it leaves the maximum fine for a first offense at 1000 but 
increases the assessment for a second offense from 1000 to 
1500 the fines for a thirdtime offender will be 2500 and 
fourthtime 10000 
