<TEXT>
a west virginia city shut down its water intakes on the ohio 
river and two ohio cities intensified treatment of water from the 
river as a fuel spill flowed slowly downstream today 
at least 75000 gallons of diesel oil gasoline and kerosene 
spilled into an allegheny river tributary upriver from pittsburgh 
on friday forcing pennsylvania cities along the river to shut 
water intakes the allegheny and monongahela rivers meet in 
pittsburgh to form the ohio river 
at east liverpool ohio water superintendent glenn woodward 
said the worst of the spill appeared to have passed by his city 
wednesday he said fuel concentrations peaked around 3 pm at 14 
or 15 parts per billion that was down to a normal level of 4 ppb 
early today 
the city treats about 3 million gallons of river water a day 
woodward said 
in steubenville ohio 25 miles downstream from east liverpool 
assistant public works director bill fabian said the spill had 
apparently arrived but lab tests of the water were not completed 
this morning 
two water intakes near the rivers surface were closed at east 
liverpool those deeper in the river remained open to draw water 
for the city of 7000 people 
its here but you cant tell it by sight or smell we started 
accelerated treatment of water at 3 yesterday afternoon and will 
continue until sunday to make sure we get the leading and tail 
edges of it fabian said 
across the river in weirton wva workers shut down the water 
intake pump wednesday said ken capozzoli a maintenance operator 
at the city water treatment plant 
we dont really know how long the wells can supply us but 
well do fine for the couple of days it should take for the spill 
to pass capozzoli said 
downtstream in wheeling wva city workers prepared to mix 
activated carbon with river water to absorb any remaining fuel 
they had pretty good luck using the carbon to remove the oil 
up in pittsburgh said phil kowalski supervisor of wheelings 
water plant we dont anticipate that people will notice any 
difference we may have to slow down our treatment process but the 
reservoirs will pick up the slack and there shouldnt be any drop 
in pressure 
