<TEXT>
defense secretary dick cheney urged congress 
today to give the pentagon more leeway to manage its budget 
contending that less intense congressional oversight would save 
money and improve defense programs 
we can do much to improve defense management by ourselves we 
could accomplish far more with the cooperation of capitol hill 
cheney said in a statement 
the defense secretarys recommendations were contained in a 
41page policy paper sent to congress today it recommended many 
changes in the way the defense department manages its programs and 
personnel as well as changes in the congressional budgetwriting 
process 
among cheneys recommendations was one that congress appropriate 
defense spending for twoyear periods instead of every year that 
would help stabilize pentagon programs by forcing more clearcut 
choices on spending priorities the report said 
if next years budget debate is only a few days away from the 
end of this years debate there is no reason to accept a negative 
decision as final the report said 
on wednesday cheney announced the pentagon was reassessing the 
need for the navys seawolf nuclear attack submarine and the 
arleigh burkeclass destroyer in light of disarmament moves and 
political changes under way in the soviet union 
in a speech to the american society of newspaper editors he 
said the move meant the pentagon was determined to readjust 
american defenses in response to global changes 
as circumstances change we will adjust the kinds of naval 
forces we need cheney said we are now looking at a smaller 
navy than we were in the early 1980s 
the united states should not however give up its global 
maritime superiority he said 
well need to control the seas regardless of what happens in 
moscow cheney said in part because the american economy is 
being more interwoven with the world economy and thus is 
increasingly dependent on the free flow of goods on the seas 
the defense secretary earlier ordered reviews of other major new 
weapons systems including the air forces b2 bomber the armys 
new light helicopter and the strategic defense initiative research 
on an antimissile defense he said results from those reviews will 
be completed within the next few weeks 
meanwhile two republican members of the senate armed services 
committee today called on president bush to limit production of the 
b2 and delay the advanced tactical fighter as part of additional 
cuts in defense spending 
we believe that the united states can meet its defense 
requirements with budget levels lower than those proposed by the 
administration said sens william cohen of maine and john mccain 
of arizona 
the administration has proposed about a 2 percent reduction in 
defense spending in each of the next five years but twice that 
amount is realistic the gop senators said by their calculations 
the current 300 billion defense budget would be reduced by about 
50 billion 
cheney gave no details of the navy program reviews a department 
spokesman bob hall said today the internal review would 
reconsider whether the seawolf subs and the burke destroyers meet 
the navys requirements taking into account such factors as 
maritime strategy cost schedules and performance 
the administration is proposing to cancel many smaller weapons 
systems and plans to cut about 50000 men and women from the 
21millionmember armed forces in 1991 the army and air force 
have taken the brunt of the reductions but cheneys remarks to the 
newspaper editors indicated the navys share of the pain may grow 
a scaling back of the navys attack submarine fleet already was 
in the wind last month vice adm daniel cooper told a house panel 
that budget constraints would limit deployments to fewer than 80 by 
the year 2000 the goal has been 100 by that date 
the first seawolf nuclear attack submarine is scheduled for 
completion in mid1995 it is designed to be quieter and have more 
weapons greater speed and more capability to kill soviet subs than 
the existing los angelesclass attack sub 
the navy is planning to buy 12 seawolfs at an average projected 
cost of 157 billion apiece 
the seawolf has been criticized for being too expensive but 
adm carlisle trost chief of naval operations wrote recently that 
the sub is required in order to ensure that we maintain an 
acceptable level of risk in the face of the continuing 
modernization of the soviet submarine force 
the burke guidedmissile destroyers are to replace the adams and 
farragut class destroyers that were built in the 1960s the 
pentagon claims the burke ships will be the most advanced and 
powerful destroyers ever built they are to be equipped with the 
hightech aegis aircraft tracking system and sophisticated missiles 
the navy plans to buy 33 of the destroyers at an average 
projected cost of 820 million apiece 
the navy is scheduled to take possession of the first destroyer 
in february 1991 eight of the new ships are under construction and 
the navy in february awarded contracts valued at a combined 11 
billion to build two more 
 
