m kennedy dmass that he and other senior advisers would urge 
bush to veto the bill if it reaches his desk 
thornburgh said the administration opposes as inconsistent 
with equal opportunity any legislation that would encourage quota 
systems or otherwise divide our society along racial lines 
the administration has been calling for a more modest version 
civil rights forces said they already have enough votes to win 
in the senate where the bill now has 40 cosponsors and the house 
as well 
the bill would ban racial discrimination in all workplace 
activities including hiring promotion demotion and firing it 
would bar onthejob harassment which the supreme court has said 
is not covered by federal law 
under the bill employers would be held liable for actions in 
which discrimination was a motivating factor even if those 
decisions had been made for nondiscriminatory reasons it also 
would provide means of locking in settlements in civil rights suits 
that otherwise might be reopened later 
the bill would expand the right of employees to challenge a 
seniority system adopted for discriminatory reasons 
perhaps the bills most controversial feature would effectively 
negate a supreme court decision last year involving a salmon 
cannery in alaska until that ruling those showing statistical 
evidence in court of hiring discrimination could force employers to 
change their practices or justify them on the basis of business 
necessity 
in the socalled wards cove decision however the court said 
that those filing discrimination suits must show that such hiring 
practices were not based upon business necessity 
in his letter to kennedy thornburgh said the administration 
is determined to help root out racial bias and bigotry but he 
said that if the measure were presented to the president in its 
current form i and other senior advisers would recommend that it 
be vetoed 
