parties in the white asian and colored or mixedrace parliaments 
allan hendrickse head of the labor party in the colored 
parliament said mandela had asked him to pull out of the talks 
with de klerk he said he would attend but ask de klerk to adjourn 
until all homeland leaders could attend 
south africa has three parliaments for whites asians and 
colored voters there is no parliament for blacks who do not have 
the vote 
the homelands were set up by the whiteminority government as 
separate areas for blacks most black opposition groups including 
anc elements oppose the homelands conservative governments and 
have helped organize resistance against them 
the anc and other opposition groups want the homelands 
reintegrated into south africa the regions have been hit by major 
unrest and the military has seized power in transkei and ciskei 
four homelands are now officially independent nations though 
they are recognized by no foreign government and six are 
classified as selfgoverning and were invited to todays talks 
the south african government says the homeland leaders must be 
included in negotiations on the countrys future 
government leaders had hoped todays meetings would help revive 
efforts to start fullscale negotiations on sharing political power 
with blacks de klerk has pledged to end apartheid 
talks set for next wednesday collapsed when the anc pulled out 
to protest the police killing of nine blacks during a march 26 
demonstration in the black township of sebokeng outside 
johannesburg the anc said it would agree to talks once the 
government brought the police under control 
mandela later agreed to a private meeting with de klerk he said 
he wanted to discuss ways to end the wave of violence across south 
africa that has claimed hundreds of lives in recent weeks 
mandela told a news conference wednesday he could not say when 
fullscale talks with the government might be rescheduled 
that will depend on the result of the discussions we are going 
to have tomorrow he said adding that the anc remained committed 
to negotiations 
we would not work so hard over three years to secure a meeting 
between the anc and the government if we were now going to turn 
around and refuse to talk mandela said 
he and other anc leaders have charged police with favoring 
buthelezis relatively conservative inkatha movement in fighting 
among rival black factions in natal province the fighting has 
claimed some 4000 lives since 1986 
police said today that the situation around edendale in natal 
province was quiet after a week of savage black factional fighting 
left at least 58 people dead the fighting pitted inkatha against 
ancbacked groups 
</TEXT>
