<TEXT>
parliament returned king baudouin to 
the throne thursday two days after he agreed to be suspended to 
avoid signing a bill legalizing abortion lawmakers urged changes 
in the law to reduce royal privileges 
there were no votes against putting the king back on the throne 
but 93 of the 338 deputies present abstained 
king baudouin a devout catholic refused to sign the abortion 
bill after it was passed by parliament last friday as the 
constitutional head of state he must sign all bills to make them 
law 
on tuesday baudouin agreed to a temporary suspension he was 
removed from the throne wednesday after which the government 
enacted the law itself 
prime minister wilfried martens said his centerleft government 
will seek changes in the constitution to prevent future refusals by 
the king on moral grounds to endorse legislation he did not 
elaborate 
but it is expected the government wants the royal powers 
already largely ceremonial reduced further 
experts said the king cannot cast aside his constitutional role 
only because he morally opposes legislation they said he can only 
lose his constitutional powers if he is physically or mentally 
unable to rule 
the bill the king opposes ended a 123year ban on abortions in 
this overwhelmingly catholic nation it allows abortions if a 
womans doctor deems a patient is in a state of distress 
opponents say this in fact makes abortion available on demand 
in short the bill represents a serious diminution of respect 
for the life of the weakest you will therefore understand i do not 
wish to be involved with that law the monarch said in a letter 
to martens last week 
to those who are surprised at my attitude i put the following 
question is it normal that i am the only belgian citizen who must 
act against his conscience in such important matters do all have 
the freedom of conscience except the king 
the belgian monarch has long opposed abortion in his 1989 
christmas message he spoke of the need for special protection 
and care for children including the correct legal protection both 
before and after birth 
vatican radio on thursday praised king baudouin for refusing to 
sign the bill into law 
in an introduction to a news report the radio station said the 
king made a noble and courageous choice that was dictated by 
his very strong moral conscience and his undisputible sense of 
statehood 
the roman catholic church opposes abortion in all circumstances 
and pope john paul ii has campaigned continuously against it there 
has been no comment from the pope on the kings move 
</TEXT>
