<TEXT>
west germany said thursday it was 
moving ahead with plans to replace the nearly worthless east german 
currency with the mighty western mark by summer amid uproar over 
the proposed exchange rate 
finance minister theo waigel confirmed newspaper reports that 
under the proposed currency union east germany would relinquish 
control of monetary policy to the west german central bank 
bundesbank 
naturally sovereignty over monetary policy in this currency 
union will lie completely with the bundesbank waigel told 
reporters 
waigel said government ministers were studying a 50page draft 
proposal for replacing the east german mark he said west germany 
would like basic agreement on the contract by next month and 
establishment of the common currency sometime this summer 
merging the german currencies is crucial to plans for rebuilding 
east germanys battered economy and to west german chancellor 
helmut kohls hope for a speedy unification of the states 
but east germans are outraged by a bundesbank recommendation 
that they get one west german mark for every two east german marks 
according to the proposal a 11 conversion rate would apply only 
on limited amounts of savings 
thousands of people rallied in east german cities thursday to 
underscore demands for a 11 exchange rate the east germans say a 
broad 2to1 rate could lead to impoverishment 
how the german currency union will be worked out is also 
worrying other european countries 
a senior dutch banker said this week that irresponsible 
promises by kohl to east germans about the terms of monetary union 
have driven european interest rates to absurdly high levels 
france italy and european economic community officials have 
been pushing for quick creation of a common eec currency and 
central bank a number of west european countries have expressed 
concern the unification process might distract west germans from 
the eecs stated goal of closer european integration 
waigel said bonn hoped to offer a finished proposal to east 
germany by midapril but that depended on when a new east german 
government was formed negotiations are under way in east berlin on 
forming a coalition government following east germanys first free 
elections on march 18 
we expect there will be negotiations with east germany after 
easter at the latest waigel said 
waigel said the bundesbanks recommendation for a 2to1 
conversion rate was not discussed by the government ministers 
thursday 
the bundesbank has said a general 1to1 swap for east german 
marks could doom many east german industries and businesses not 
only by increasing the value of their debt but by boosting the 
purchasing power of east germans who might then start buying 
superior west german products 
the west german government says it is examining the bundesbank 
proposal but has not disclosed what it will offer east germany 
handelsblatt a widely respected west german financial 
newspaper said the government would choose a 1to1 rate for wages 
and pensions and increase the amount of savings that can be 
exchanged at that favorable rate 
but even if wages and pensions are converted at 1to1 
corporate debt and other businessrelated aggregates will still be 
exchanged at a 2to1 rate the newspaper said 
</TEXT>
