americans took out 34 billion more in 
consumer credit than they retired in february but the pace slowed 
because of slackening demand for car loans the government said 
thursday 
the federal reserve said consumer credit increased at a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 57 percent down from januarys 
revised 64 percent pace the january rate was reported last month 
to have been 59 percent 
consumer credit which includes all consumer loans except 
mortgages was up 73 percent in december 
automobile loans advanced in february to a seasonally adjusted 
889 million in february that represented an annual rate of 37 
percent less than half the 84 percent jump in january when sales 
incentives were reinstated the incentives continued in february 
but consumer response failed to keep up 
without incentives auto loans had fallen 04 percent in 
december 
credit card debt rose 485 million 29 percent at an annual 
rate slightly faster pace than januarys 18 percent gain but much 
slower than the 237 percent rate during the december holiday 
shopping period 
bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate were up 
121 percent an increase of 204 billion after gains of 9 
percent in january and 3 percent in december 
borrowing for mobile homes continued its recent downward trend 
off 2 million or 01 percent with the exception of a 28 percent 
gain in september mobile home credit has fallen each month since 
february 1989 
the various changes left total consumer debt at the end of 
february at 7237 billion 
