<TEXT>
one in three american adults say they or 
someone in their family have sought help from a psychiatrist or a 
psychologist according to a survey released thursday 
yet the survey also found among those polled widespread 
opposition to putting any kind of mental health facility or housing 
for people with mental illness in their neighborhoods 
miles shore director of the robert wood johnson foundations 
program on chronic mental illness said he was encouraged that 
nearly 90 percent describe mental illness as a serious health 
problem and many believe it can be treated 
but he said the survey points out a contradiction in what he 
called the notinmybackyard or nimby phenomenon 
on the one hand people do object to siting these facilities 
in their back yard on the other hand over half recognize that 
mental illness can improve and that keeping up a normal life 
which includes community living will help with that 
improvement he said 
the survey found that 74 percent of those polled believe 
correctly that anyone can become mentally ill and that mental 
illness can be cured and 53 percent believe that keeping up a 
normal life in the community will help a person with mental illness 
get better 
but two in three believe there is a lot of stigma attached to 
mental illness according to the survey which was commissioned by 
the foundation 
it also found that those with higher incomes were more likely to 
oppose placing mental health facilities in their neighborhoods 
members of families with income of more than 50000 were twice 
as likely to oppose these facilities in their neighborhoods and 
the strongest opponents tended to be older well educated 
professional men who were married and owned a home in a large city 
or a suburb of a large city shore said 
the foundations program on chronic mental illness commissioned 
the study to help in its efforts to encourage acceptance of housing 
for people with mental illnesses 
the study was based on telephone interviews with 1300 adults 
between dec 1 and dec 11 1989 
it was funded by the foundation the american psychiatric 
association the national institute for mental health and the pew 
charitable trusts 
</TEXT>
