<TEXT>
lowincome families that receive food stamps 
will keep most of those benefits despite an increase in the minimum 
wage a senior agriculture department official said thursday 
every case is different but most food stamp recipients will 
keep at least 64 cents in benefits for each dollar they gain in 
wages said assistant secretary catherine bertini who oversees 
usda food and consumer services 
the food stamp program is not an alternative to work she 
said in a statement we want to encourage people to work earn 
money and support themselves and their families 
the federal hourly minimum wage rose to from 335 an hour april 
1 and will increase again next april 1 to 425 an hour 
food stamp benefits are allocated on the basis of several 
factors including household size and net income as determined by 
deducting expenses for such items as housing utilities and day 
care 
bertini cited an example of a family of three claiming the 
maximum deduction for housing earning 580 per month in wages and 
receiving 207 in food stamps under the new minimum wage law the 
familys earnings would increase by 78 to 658 per month while 
food stamp benefits would be reduced by 19 per month 
that would total 787 per month under the old minimum wage and 
846 under the new a net gain of 67 per month she said 
the gain in wages more than makes up for the loss in food 
stamps bertini said in fact for each new dollar earned with 
the new minimum wage this household would keep 76 cents in food 
stamp benefits 
more than 19 million people get benefits under the food stamp 
program which is estimated to cost 148 billion this year 
