the military in the nominally 
independent homeland of venda overthrew the government thursday and 
said the area should be reincorperated into south africa radio 
reports said 
col gabriel ramushwana 48 deputy chief of the venda defense 
force announced the coup in a broadcast over radio thohoyandou he 
said the government of president frank ravele had been corrupt and 
unstable and the country had been plagued by lawlessness boycotts 
and human rights violations 
the independent south african press association confirmed the 
report and said there was singing and dancing in the streets of 
venda as news of the coup spread 
the governmentrun south african broadcasting corp said ravele 
and his cabinet resigned it said nothing about a coup 
raveles government was the target of mass protests in recent 
weeks that shut down schools transportation and government 
services 
the protesters demanded that the 2500squaremile republic be 
reincorporated into south africa this would allow venda residents 
to receive the benefits that go with south african citizenship 
they also demanded an investigation into allegations some cabinet 
members participated in ritual murder and witchcraft 
several of the demonstrations were dispersed by police gunfire 
and there were reports of casualties although the exact number is 
uncertain 
ramushwana made no mention of raveles fate he told everyone to 
go home and return to work on monday friday is a national holiday 
in venda and the rest of south africa 
the coup occurred thursday morning said a venda businessman who 
spoke on condition of anonymity by noon telephone connections had 
been cut and roadblocks were set up on all routes out of the 
homeland 
there were no immediate reports of fighting or casualties 
there are four nominally independent homelands in south africa 
and three have experience military coups in the last 2 years 
an attempt at a coup in bophuthatswana failed in february 1988 
after the president lucas mangope was rescued by south african 
police 
residents of the tribal homelands are denied south african 
citizenship and the residential pension and work rights that 
accompany the citizenship the homelands are not recognized as 
independent by any other nations 
south africa also has six tribal homelands that have refused to 
accept independence 
ravele was not among the homeland leaders expected at talks 
thursday in cape town with south african president fw de klerk 
only the nonindependent homelands were to have been represented 
venda is in the far northeast corner of south africa adjoining 
kruger national park with a small strip of south african territory 
separating it from the zimbabwe border 
