<TEXT>
israelis are increasingly demanding electoral 
reforms as cases of politicians offering favors for support to form 
a coalition government become more blatant 
there is a complete breakdown in trust said law professor 
uriel reichman who is leading the reform campaign politicians 
are using their power to enhance their own political ambitions by 
bribing parties and legislators 
examples abound 
hours before he left the finance ministry last month labor 
party leader shimon peres gave 35 million to religious 
institutions belonging to an ultraorthodox faction he hoped would 
support his bid to become prime minister 
the rival likud offered a 25 million guarantee to ensure its 
promise of a new cabinet post to economics minister yitzhak modai 
who had threatened to defect to labor the money did not reach the 
10 million modai demanded 
both labor and likud archrivals in the race to form a 
government adopted a lastminute budget amendment march 30 giving 
110 million to religious institutions triple last years 
allocations 
israelis are used to a certain amount of dealmaking in coalition 
negotiations as israels political system often makes small 
parties the kingmakers between the two major parties 
but the desperate steps taken by both the leftleaning labor and 
the rightwing likud have brought an unprecedented call for reform 
newspaper editorials student groups womens groups and even 
some politicians have urged a change in the system 
the most dramatic appeal has come from two army reserve officers 
who began a hunger strike thursday in a park opposite parliament 
the same day peres announced he had succeeded in piecing together 
a ruling coalition to replace the one that collapsed over 
disagreement on middle east peace moves 
the strikers have since been joined by eight others in their 
fast they met with thousands of wellwishers and collected 25000 
signatures calling for electoral reform 
ohad limor a lieutenant in the army reserves said he joined 
the hunger strikers after parliament approved the extra funds for 
the religious parties 
when i heard this i said thats it no more this is not 
something you see on television this is my life said limor 25 
sitting on a beach chair outside a tent 
most of those opposed to the current political system have only 
vague notions about what should replace it but there is nothing 
that could be worse than what we have now limor said 
reichman who says he has support from 68 israeli mayors made 
three demands direct election of the prime minister direct 
election of at least half the legislators and adoption of a bill of 
rights 
the current system has israelis voting for parties not 
individual candidates any party capturing 1 percent of the total 
vote in the country wins a seat in the 120member knesset 
reichmans public committee for a constitution for israel and 
other protest groups called a rally in tel aviv for saturday and a 
wide range of organizations have urged members to attend 
likud facing the possibility of a laborled government jumped 
on the bandwagon thursday it offered to set up a transition 
government with labor to legislate reform including the direct 
election of the prime minister 
the reformers chances for success are up against a long history 
of broken promises from legislators who benefit from the existing 
unbalanced system 
but reichman and others were optimistic that the tide could not 
be turned back this is a critical moment in the history of the 
country there is hope that from the present chaos a new chapter in 
our history will be written 
</TEXT>
