<TEXT>
a tearful but defiant leona helmsley vowed 
thursday i am not going to jail after her attorneys asked a 
judge to dismiss state income tax evasion charges against her 
the 69yearold selfproclaimed hotel queen was convicted last 
year of federal income tax fraud and sentenced to four years in 
prison but is free on bond pending appeal 
she still faces state charges that she her husband and two 
former employees falsified 3 million worth of business and tax 
records from 1982 to 1986 
mrs helmsley sat quietly through the proceedings in manhattans 
state supreme court but surrounded by reporters as she left the 
courthouse she again protested her innocence 
enough is enough she said in a hoarse voice occasionally 
choked by tears i am not going to jail ive done nothing wrong 
my only crime is that im leona helmsley for that im guilty 
her attorney sandor frankel told justice john ak bradley 
that his client has already been enormously punished by the 
federal prosecution 
he also argued that the state charges constituted double 
jeopardy the federal indictment contained at least 10 charges 
specifically dealing with state income taxes he said 
the government should not be able to take multiple bites out 
of the human hide he said 
assistant attorney general alfredo mendez said that the 
188count state indictment contained many other charges not 
prosecuted by federal authorities 
it is in fact in the interest of justice that new york tax 
cheats be brought to justice he said 
the judge asked frankel if i dismiss the indictment would 
not the public conclude that theres one law for the rich and 
another for the poor 
the fact that were here judge frankel replied isnt 
that saying there is one law for the wealthy wellknown and 
vilified and another for everyone else 
frankel also asked bradley to allow a pretrial hearing to 
establish whether the indictment originated through a tainted 
chain from testimony mrs helmsley gave under a grant of immunity 
in a separate 1985 investigation of sales tax fraud 
her attorneys maintain that leaks to the media a year later 
about her testimony prompted mrs helmsleys enemies to contact 
reporters about other activities which led to the state and 
federal investigations 
bradley said he would rule on the motions on may 17 
mrs helmsley faces up to four years in state prison if 
convicted 
her husband harry 80 was found mentally incompetent to stand 
trial in federal court and wants to have the state charges against 
him dismissed on the same grounds an april 30 court date was set 
to address that issue 
in december mrs helmsley rejected an offer to serve a prison 
term concurrently with her federal sentence in exchange for 
pleading guilty to evading 750000 in state income taxes 
the two former executives joseph v licari and frank j turco 
have accepted similar deals 
