<TEXT>
twothirds of defendants charged with felonies 
in 39 of the nations largest counties were released from police 
custody pending court action the justice department said in a 
study released thursday 
the sampling of 11063 felony cases filed in february 1988 
showed that 66 percent of the defendants were released on bail 
bond or their own recognizance while awaiting trial or ther 
dispositions of their cases 
the study showed that 31 percent were held in jail pending trial 
because they were unable to post bail another 4 percent of the 
defendants were ordered held without bail following their 
arraignments 
the statistics gathered from local courts by the justice 
departments bureau of justice statistics was intended to be a 
sampling of the disposition of felony charges in 75 of the nations 
largest counties 
the study tracked the felony cases from initial filing to 
disposition in courts in 39 local jurisdictions including the 
district of columbia 
of the defendants accused of violent offenses 59 percent were 
released on bail or their own recognizance sixtyone percent of 
murder defendants were kept in custody while 39 percent were 
released on bail or personal recognizance twentysix percent of 
murder suspects were ordered held without bail 35 percent could 
not post enough money to obtain their release 
among accused rapists 55 percent were released while 45 percent 
were detained pending disposition of their cases fiftytwo percent 
of robbery defendants were released as were 66 percent of those 
accused of assault 
seventytwo percent of defendants charged with sale or 
possession of illegal drugs were released from custody while 
awaiting trial the study said 
bail is requested by prosecutors to guarantee that a defendant 
will appear in court for subsequent proceedings and does not 
necessarily reflect the seriousness of the charges against the 
defendant 
to determine if there is a risk of flight judges traditionally 
consider whether the defendant has strong ties to the community 
through relatives or friends 
some jurisdictions such as the district of columbia have 
preventive detention statutes that allow defendants charged with 
serious crimes to be held without bail 
the statistics gathered in the study indicate that defendants 
previously convicted of violent offenses were less likely to be 
released on bail than suspects who had records of other types of 
offenses 
only 33 percent of defendants who already had been convicted of 
violent felony crimes such as rape or murder were released on bail 
by contrast 62 percent of defendants with prior felony drug 
convictions were released on bail 
according to the study 76 percent of those released on bail 
appeared for all court proceedings while 24 percent missed a court 
date 
of the defendants for whom bench warrants were issued 16 
percent were eventually returned to court and 8 percent were 
fugitives after one year 
besides the district of columbia the data was collected from 
cases in maricopa county ariz los angeles orange sacramento 
san bernardino san diego and santa clara counties in california 
broward dade duval hillsborough palm beach pinellas counties 
in florida fulton county ga honolulu hawaii cook county 
ill suffolk county mass wayne county mich st louis mo 
essex county nj bronx erie kings monroe new york and queens 
counties in new york hamilton county ohio allegheny montgomery 
counties in pennsylvania and philadelphia shelby county tenn 
harris and tarrant counties in texas and dallas salt lake utah 
fairfax county va king county wash and milwaukee wis 
</TEXT>
