federal agents raided highpriced call girl 
escort services around the country culminating a twoyear 25 
million moneylaundering sting authorities said thursday 
these are not streetlevel hookers the average receipts were 
for 800 to 1000 an evening said maurice dettmer chief of 
criminal investigations for the internal revenue service 
the raids on more than 40 escort services late wednesday and 
early thursday culminated what investigators called the nations 
largest concerted attack on upscale prostitution 
the probe targeted escort services that accept credit cards 
dettmer said agents created phony businesses in atlanta and in 
tampa to process and disguise more than 25000 creditcard receipts 
for escort services from 23 cities in 15 states he said 
the businesses given the name sunset enterprises often 
disguised the creditcard charges for copying services or converted 
the charges to cash or loans for escort services or massage 
parlors authorities said 
the 25 million in charged payments represented only about 
onequarter of the 10 million to 12 million the escort services 
took in in gross earnings dettmer said 
agents charged a 13 percent to 18 percent fee said tampa police 
spokesman steve cole typically a call girl would collect 500 
the escort service 300 and the agents 200 cole said 
local authorities said the clients included politicians 
entertainers athletes business executives using company credit 
cards doctors lawyers and clergymen but they gave no details of 
the clients 
we expect a lot of bosses and wives will be looking through 
receipts this evening to see if they say sunset enterprises not to 
mention nervous businessmen cole said 
federal and state agents armed with warrants searched the 
escortservice companies for records of prostitution activities 
income and expenses and names of customers and their credit card 
charges said us attorney robert genzman 
also sought was evidence relative to alleged moneylaundering 
activities by escortservice operators to conceal an estimated 10 
million in gross earnings in alleged creditcard fraud genzman 
said 
authorities recently made three arrests in california and one 
each in fort lauderdale atlanta and dallas during the 
investigation after the raids more arrests were expected 
authorities said 
they said federal moneylaundering and taxevasion charges could 
be expected state racketeering and organized crime charges also 
could be filed 
if there are substantial amounts of charges for escort 
services on a corporate or business credit card that would be a 
strong likelihood theres been false tax deductions and they may 
hear from the irs said dettmer 
agents used the telephone directory to find escort services that 
accepted credit cards the reason they take credit cards is 
because businessmen traveling have company credit cards companies 
then deduct it as a business expense dettmer said 
most escort services would pay to disguise creditcard charges 
as going to a copying service said an agent who worked on the 
operation in savannah ga 
