sen bob packwood said thursday a special 
provision of the endangered species act could allow logging to 
continue in the forests where the northern spotted owl lives even 
if the bird is declared threatened or endangered 
lawmakers in the pacific northwest are concerned that efforts to 
save the owl from extinction will have a disastrous impact on the 
regional economy because large tracts of federal forests could be 
put off limits to loggers 
packwood rore said in an interview thursday the special 
provision in the act allowing a committee to consider possible 
economic hardship may provide a way to continue logging 
when the fish and wildlife service decides on the listing it 
is allowed to consider only biological factors but this special 
committee can also consider economic factors packwood said 
the special committee would consist of the us secretaries of 
agriculture interior and army the administrator of the 
environmental protection agency the chairman of the council of 
economic advisors the head of the national oceanographic and 
atmospheric administration and one individual from each of the 
states effected 
they would have the power to set aside the listing in 
essence they could allow whatever economic activities to continue 
even if the species is listed packwood said 
they would have to be sure to try not to affect the species 
but they would have the power to allow the continuation of logging 
if they decided the payments to schools the jobs of mill workers 
and the economic viability of oregon are more important than the 
owl he said 
a request for the convening of the committee can be made by the 
governor of a state effected a federal agency involved in the case 
or an interested party packwood said 
i dont know if i qualify as an interested party but i dont 
think we would have any trouble finding someone to make the 
request im going to call the governor of oregon and talk about 
this he said 
brock evans vice president of the national audubon society 
said he doubted the special committee process would have any impact 
if the fish and wildlife service decides to list the owl as 
threatened or endangered a decision due by june 23 
