<TEXT>
boneweakening osteoporosis cannot be 
prevented by gorging on calciumrich foods university of michigan 
researchers said thursday 
we found that adults with high calcium intakes didnt lose 
less bone and that adults with low calcium intakes didnt lose more 
bone said stanley garn a professor of nutrition at the 
universitys school of public health 
the more bone you have the more you have to lose he said 
in a news release from the university you dont create more bone 
by stuffing calcium into young women any more than you create more 
muscle by stuffing steak into football players 
the study was based on comparisons of xray measurements of 745 
adult mens and womens hand bones taken from 196365 and again in 
1985 the ann arbor university said the subjects also reported 
their eating habits focusing on calcium and phosphorous intake 
osteoporosis a softening of the bones tends to begin with 
women in their early 40s and with men in their 50s regardless of 
their calcium intake the researchers said in a study presented 
thursday at a joint meeting of the american association of physical 
anthropology and the human biology council in miami 
the results were consistent with earlier studies in which garn 
and other researchers found that entire populations with high 
calcium intake as part of their everyday diet suffered bone loss 
comparable to groups eating a predominantly lowcalcium ricebased 
diet 
dr richard mazess professor emeritus of medical physics at the 
university of wisconsin endorsed the findings 
theyre entirely in accord with the rest of the scientific 
evidence to date mazess said in a telephone interview the 
overwhelming evidence is that calcium has very little to do with 
bone loss except in people with marginal intake under 400 
milligrams a day 
the average americans diet supplies 600800 milligrams of 
calcium daily mazess said calcium supplements might benefit those 
receiving less he said but increasing consumption of dairy 
products the most common source of calcium carries higher levels 
of cholesterol and coronary risk 
exercise may help women prevent the disease but the most 
effective treatment is estrogen therapy beginning with menopause 
when the loss of bone mass tends to accelerate mazess said its 
not a calciumdeficiency disease he said 
the michigan study also found no relationship between cigarette 
smoking alcohol or the use of antihypertensive drugs and the 
amount of bone loss 
</TEXT>
