<TEXT>
a loving grandmother wouldnt give up despite 
what doctors said and helped her injured grandson learn to breathe 
on his own again 
through her persistence and doctors doubt dolores anderson 
helped 9yearold lortray gordon learn to breathe for up to 10 
hours a day without his ventilator 
they said there was no way this kid could live i refused to 
hear that stuff mrs anderson said 
they said hed always be on a ventilator she said they 
wanted me to put tray away into an old folks home i said no 
way forget it 
janna jacobs of the national spinal cord injury association near 
boston said it is unusual for a family member to accomplish what 
mrs anderson did 
what a brave lady ms jacobs said i admire her spirit 
and courage 
the credit belongs to the grandma said dr jim hillman one 
of the boys doctors 
while visiting relatives in vero beach in november 1986 the boy 
darted into traffic and was hit by a car his injury is called a 
hangmans fracture because that is where a noose hits in a 
hanging the fracture was in an area of the spinal cord that 
controls breathing 
he spent two months in a coma in a vero beach hospital then was 
transferred to a tampa hospital where he underwent six operations 
in seven months he then went to a spinal cord center in atlanta 
for six months 
a lot of people had written him off said peggy berger 
director of nurses at west shore hospital where gordon later went 
for treatment his grandmother said no youre not going to put 
him aside she was right 
mrs anderson said she talked to gordon about taking him off the 
ventilator he couldnt say anything but she said he indicated he 
wanted to try 
on the first try she took the air supply away for five minutes 
his diaphragm the muscle that moves the lungs up and down had 
atrophied from disuse but strengthened as she increased the time 
off the machine each day 
in two months when the boy could be off the ventilator an hour 
and a half a day mrs anderson told doctors and social workers 
what she had done 
everybody was in shock they said he cant breathe on his 
own i said come over and see for yourselves 
to help his recovery doctors sent gordon to west shore 
hospital which specializes in the rehabilitation of patients on 
ventilators after five months he can breathe on his own long 
enough to make it through a school day 
mrs anderson is appealing for donations to pay for a van to 
carry gordon to school in hillsborough county where officials say 
he will be the school systems first student to need the assistance 
of a ventilator 
