<TEXT>
a federal judge ruled thursday that the 
citys program for giving minorityowned businesses preferred 
status is unconstitutional 
the socalled setaside program called for at least 15 
percent of budgeted city contracts were go to minorityowned 
businesses and 10 percent to femaleowned businesses 
businesses in which minorities or women held at least 51 percent 
ownership also were eligible for setaside contracts 
a coalition of contractors sued in 1989 contending that the 
program discriminated against them because of their nonminority 
status 
us district judge louis c bechtles order permanently enjoins 
the setaside program he said it violates the fourteenth amendment 
of the us constitution which guarantees the rights of citizens 
city solictor charisse r lillie said the city would appeal and 
is asking for a stay 
philadelphia contracting firm owner barbera bushing said i 
think thats really too bad the maleowned businesses really dont 
care about hiring women 
its already hard for women to get into it this decision 
makes it even tougher she added 
john h widman an attorney for the contractors said he did not 
think minority firms would be hurt by the decision 
now we can focus on what contracting is all about and that is 
skills price and expericence widman said 
mayor w wilson goode has praised the program which was 
established in 1982 under former mayor william j green 
bechtle said he based his decision on a 1989 us supreme court 
ruling that threw out richmond vas program of setting aside 30 
percent of city construction contracts for minorityowned 
businesses 
the supreme court ruled that past discrimination would have to 
be well documented before a program could constitutionally be 
enacted to correct discrimination they ruled that discrimination 
did not exist simply because 50 percent of the richmond population 
was black and only twothirds of 1 percent of the contracts went to 
blackowned business 
philadelphias minority setaside program was aimed at 
correcting a pattern of past and present racial sexual and 
economic discrimination according to the ordinances preamble 
