extinctionyal armory craftsmen and five assistants restore and 
conserve the 40000 pieces of armor in the tower collection 
smith 62 will retire in 1992 and is passing on his knowledge 
of makin 
the two rog and repairing armor to his 26yearold son christopher 
behind a bright red door away from the crown jewels and the 2 
million tourists who flock to the 900yearold tower each year the 
smiths work together on a replica of a knights fighting helmet 
made in northern italy in 1460 
their one concession to modernity is a propane torch all other 
materials and methods are authentic to the time 
medieval armorers used cumbersome coal forges a propane torch 
makes it easier to work on those awkward lancerests and chanfrons 
we had a small forge for awhile but it blew up a couple of 
times and with a gallery directly above us it wouldnt have been 
practical ted smith explained 
for the rouns to disband the 
assembly and have new elections 
ibrahim nafei a mubarak confidant and editor of the leading 
newspaper alahram expressed the government position there can 
be no invalidation of the peoples assembly 
the constitutional argument is part of a political tugofwar 
that began almost as soon as mubarak took office 
a major issue has been the regular extension of an emergency 
enacted after sadat was killed it gives the executive branch wide 
powers of arrest and search without warrant and bans strikes and 
demonstrations 
opposition parties want the law scrapped but the government 
says it is a vital tool against moslem extremists the latest 
extension runs until spring 1991 
mubarak has not said whether he will disband the peoples 
assembly an aide mustafa elfiki said the president will act 
at the right time in the light of litigation indicating he might 
await the constitutional court ruling 
the constitution gives a president the right to dissolve 
parliament only with the electorates approval in a referendum 
in 1987 mubarak called a referendum before the court upheld 
khalids suit against parts of the election law the voters 
endorsed dissolution and elections two months later in april 
after the peoples assembly nominated mubarak for a second 
sixyear term in october 1987 voters approved him in another 
referendum 
at the time the political consensus that mubarak dissolved 
parliament quickly because the presidential nomination was nearly 
at hand this time no such urgent business is pending 
</TEXT>
