<DOCNO> AP900405-0212 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after nine years of bickering 42 lawsuits 
design changes and false starts a 25 billion plan to sanitize 
tawdry times square is about to become reality 
or is it the 42nd street development project says 
groundbreaking is in sight opponents say it might never come to 
pass 
is it alive or dead i dont think anybody knows said kent 
barwick president of the municipal art society a nonprofit 
organization that analyzes and addresses aesthetic issues affecting 
new york city particularly architecture and planning 
not a single spade of dirt has been turned in the 
governmentbacked project but the mere promise of it has helped 
trigger brisk construction by private developers elsewhere in the 
neighborhood 
critics say that means the development project has served its 
purpose and should just fade away 
the projects parent the state urban development corp wants 
to replace rundown buildings in the historic entertainment 
district with four office towers ranging from 32 to 57 stories and 
glitzed up with signs lights and mirrors a merchandise mart and 
new hotel are on the back burner 
the idea is to discourage drug dealers muggers con artists and 
prostitutes 
theres a sense that times square has become a more menacing 
place said sociologist william kornblum of the city university 
graduate center who has studied the district for 12 years 
in 1988 2246 felony crimes were reported on 42nd street 
between broadway and eighth avenue an area of just over a block 
safety was a major concern of madeline dominique danthony 
proprietor of the harmony burlesque theater when she moved three 
years ago to the artsy tribeca area near wall street her landlord 
had sold the building at 48th street and broadway where shed done 
business for 10 years 
just because im in the burlesque business doesnt mean i like 
42nd street she said i was offered a rental situation there 
but didnt take it because im not walking down that block 
danthony who strives to keep her business tasteful no 
barkers unseemly pictures or neon girls girls girls signs 
outside said its wrong to blame the crime on the sex industry 
volume is what attracts crime she said when you put all 
those places together you create a hightraffic situation drug 
pushers pickpockets they get lost in the crowd 
when i left times square i noticed immediately that my good 
customers stayed with me and the riffraff stayed in times square 
my girls said the same thing she said 
barwick blames the blight on real estate speculation 
since everybody had been led to believe for generations that 
the area would be creamed to make way for highrise offices people 
werent taking care of their buildings he said 
still critics say flooding times square with office workers in 
suits would douse the vitality and offbeat flavor of one of the 
worlds most famous entertainment districts 
i think the times square cacophony is a delight a visual 
riot said stephen f wilder a member of community board 5 a 
volunteer advisory board of area residents and business people 
its truly the one place in the city historically where 
different classes and races and kinds of people came together 
said barwick cities need such places for their spirit and soul 
and their economies 
times square still has a national and international cachet 
agreed kornblum one hears when you interview people on the 
