<TEXT>
an unexpected resurrection of nations from 
totalitarianism has swept eastern europe in recent months 
reintroducing longtrampled freedoms and reducing international 
distrust the first story in a fivepart easter series 
resurrection of nations examines the surprising upheaval and 
its religious threads 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in a blink the landscape heaved and the world changed people 
could hardly believe it amazed incredulous they saw a new 
reality dawning over the earth surmounting old fears and fatalism 
the grim immutable facts of their existence were suddenly not 
what they had seemed 
that baffled astonishment among eastern europeans at their burst 
from bondage also resonates in the recorded reaction to the 
resurrection of christ and the liberating word of easter 
it has indeed been miraculous a miracle that happened in the 
souls of people said the rev john meyendorff a scholar of the 
russianderived but independent orthodox church in america it 
has been a resurrection from a long deadening of individual 
creativity and the godgiven dignity of being human for millions of 
people 
no one could have predicted its suddenness and sweep he said 
i never thought id live to see it people are finding it hard to 
believe 
an idle tale he apostles scoffed at first reports of 
christs resurrection it made no sense the buried restored to 
life they couldnt conceive of it until it confronted them 
directly and plainly 
likewise it had seemed impossible that half a continent 
coumenon the berlin wall that barrier of cold war that for three 
decades had divided humanity literally and figuratively at last 
came tumbling down nov 9 
among rejoicing throngs an east german friar said with a 
chuckle the iron curtain is not so much iron anymore 
the walls demise and the rest of the whirlwind that freed 
nations and eased superpower antagonisms symbolically reflected a 
scripture passage on christs crucifixion and resurrection 
for he is our peace who has made us both one and has broken 
down the dividing wall of hostility 
the changes came in tidal profusion in the soviet union and its 
satellite countries one after another like some pentup force 
breaking loose uncontainable overflowing toppling tyrants 
unleashing multitudes from their chains 
almost magically the changes came generally without violence 
in socalled soft or velvet revolutions 
not by might nor by power but by my spirit says the lord of 
hosts the biblical prophet zechariah said 
just as christs resurrection defied logic so on another plane 
did the breakthrough of nations the sweeping transformation of 
1989 contradicted all prior analyses and predictions it went 
against the prognostications of the keenest thinkers and the 
gloomiest doomsayers 
it is difficult to think of any series of developments more 
astonishing said roman catholic historiantheologian richard 
mcbrien 
harvard historian richard pipes wrote the recent events there 
have surpassed the wildest fantasies of any observer of soviet 
affairs who was willing to go on record 
the facts those grim facts of life in the soviet bloc were 
suddenly turned upside down just as the crucified arose eastern 
europes long coerced and silenced millions lurched forth into the 
exhilarating yet bewilderingly unfamiliar light of new freedom 
we are like children waking from a nightmare in the middle of 
the night emilian mercan a member of the hastily formed 
provisional government of craiova romania said after the 
middecember collapse of the harsh ceausescu regime all we want 
is reassurance that it wont happen again 
gradually the countries of eastern europe are permitting such 
gifts to the spirit as the freedoms to speak out assemble 
organize and vote but the daybreak atmosphere like life itself 
is loaded with risk and uncertainty 
it happened so quickly said petar darliev a bulgarian 
imprisoned for nine years who at 74 is helping plan the countrys 
first multiparty elections in 45 years scheduled for june the 
hard part starts now 
it is a peculiar drama which no earthling could have 
written said previously imprisoned playwright vaclav havel 
chosen to be czechoslovakias president by a new parliament in 
december general elections are set for june 8 
of the times before the crucifixion the apostle paul wrote 
we know that the whole world has been groaning in travail until 
now 
for much of the 20th century the globe has been groaning 
caught in a tightening nuclear stranglehold with no apparent way 
to escape 
but the metamorphosis provided by christ has come in a 
different order for nations writing after christ rose from the 
