the broad turn to democracy started earlier and proceeded more 
gradually in poland and hungary 
in poland visited three times by the pope stubborn strikes and 
demonstrations in 1980 gave birth to the solidarity labor union 
the first in eastern europe the union backed by the church was 
outlawed in 1982 under martial law 
its leader lech walesa was arrested and other union leaders 
were driven underground but the union maintained pressure on the 
government the pressure coupled with a disastrous economy forced 
negotiations last year that led to the june 4 elections when 
solidarity swept into control of parliament 
in may 1988 hungary ousted its puppet party boss janos kadar 
who had ruled for 32 years ever since soviet tanks crushed a 
hungarian uprising in 1956 
a national catharsis came june 16 1989 when bodies of executed 
leaders of the revolt including that of prime minister imre nagy 
were exhumed from unmarked graves and reburied with honors 
in january 1989 hungary cut the electrified barbed wire along 
its border with austria opening it to vacationing east germans and 
others fleeing communist oppression 
all soviet troops are to be withdrawn from hungary by june 30 
1991 and last months multiparty elections were seen as the advent 
of working democracy 
god gives power to the faint wrote the biblical prophet 
isaiah they shall renew their strength they shall mount up with 
wings like eagles 
