<TEXT>
when david grossman got married a distant aunt 
turned up at the ceremony with a bandaid hiding the number 
tattooed on her arm 
it was as though being a concentration camp survivor was 
something she should hide something that brought shame and should 
not surface at a happy celebration it was awful the israeli 
novelist recalls 
memories such as that permeate see under love the 
36yearold authors hugely ambitious attempt to portray the 
holocaust as it has filtered through to israels postholocaust 
generation the sons and daughters who had no direct experience of 
the horror yet are profoundly influenced by its legacy 
published in the original hebrew in 1986 the novel has just 
appeared in english to rare acclaim from british critics 
see under love is a sprawling book innovatively 
constructed bursting with literary magic and in the end strangely 
upbeat the opening 86page section alone is what george steiner in 
the sunday times called one of the great feats in modern 
fiction 
it tells of momik a lonely precocious 9yearold growing up in 
the israel of 1959 among parents and neighbors who survived the 
holocaust an ordinary kid would hunger to know the facts of life 
momik searches for the facts of death why will nobody tell him 
what exactly happened over there what is this thing they call 
the nazi beast what are those tattooed numbers secret codes 
momik tried everything to wash grandfathers arm but the 
number stayed fixed which gave momik an idea that maybe the number 
wasnt written from the outside but from the inside and that 
convinced him more than ever that there was somebody there inside 
grandfather and the others too maybe which is how they call out 
for help 
someone tells him that the nazi beast could come out of any 
kind of animal if it got the right care and nourishment so he 
keeps caged rodents in the cellar trying to make the beast spring 
from one of them and be tamed 
in the second section momik is a young author trying to write 
about the holocaust he is convinced that he has finally grasped 
its meaning that he must be tough unloving and pessimistic to 
be ready when it happens again 
if i ever had a child momik tells his wife the first 
thing i would do in the morning would be to slap his face just 
like that so hell know theres no justice in this world only 
strife 
part 3 is about momiks grandfather anshel wasserman once a 
famous writer of childrens stories who is now in a concentration 
camp neigel the nazi commandant who grew up on wassermans books 
makes him tell him a story every night wassermans cunningly woven 
stories coax a spark of humanity out of neigel that drives the nazi 
to suicide 
this sequence leads into the final section in which grossman 
attempts to tie the threads together in an inventive encyclopedic 
format and deliver the books ultimate message of love and hope 
the book is full of allusions doublemeanings and magical 
fantasies of the wandering jew as a salmon forever swimming toward 
its beginnings of a messiah whose gift is to relieve people of 
their past of the baby kazik who lives an entire human life from 
birth to death in 24 hours of anshel wasserman himself blessed 
or cursed with a strange inability to be killed by gas or bullets 
comparisons to guenther grass salman rushdie and gabriel garcia 
marquez are inevitable and have been made by some critics 
writing about the holocaust is not easy one of the finest 
survivorauthors the israeli novelist aharon appelfeld has made 
his mark in holocaust literature by writing not about the 
atrocities but around them believing that the holocaust is a 
flame too hot to be touched 
thats perhaps because he went through the fire grossman 
said in an interview during a visit to london my feeling was 
that my own life would go up in flames if i didnt put my hand in 
the fire because there was a fire there all the time and i knew i 
wouldnt understand it until i put my hand in it 
grossman and his parents did not go through the holocaust but 
like momik he grew up with these silences always around me 
the israel of his youth was not yet ready to delve into the horror 
it was too busy absorbing immigrants building an army making the 
desert bloom its role model was the fighting israeli not the jew 
being led to the gas chamber 
incidents such as the one involving the aunt and the bandaid 
were typical he says of how the survivors themselves 
collaborated with this denial they felt themselves to be the 
symbol of the weak jew in this new advanced slightly 
arrogant militaristic israel 
at school he says i learned more about the french revolution 
than i did about the holocaust but the complexes rubbed off all 
the same 
i know how much i have to fight against things in myself 
says the bespectacled slightly built israeli i also feel the 
footprints of this fear of annihilation this suspicion toward 
everyone i have to invest so much energy to not distrust people 
to take them on faith to enjoy life just to live 
clearly he succeeded his other wellknown book the yellow 
wind was an agonizing account of palestinian life under israeli 
occupation and he has campaigned hard for israel to talk to the 
palestinians he was sacked from his job at israel radio over an 
order forbidding the broadcast of plo voices and reinstated after 
a public outcry government censors briefly barred schoolage 
audiences from viewing a play based on the yellow wind 
we survived the holocaust in order to live and now we live 
in order to survive he says to live you have to be flexible 
to accept changes and turn them to your advantage the survivor 
cant accept changes to open up to take a risk these are 
abilities that have atrophied among us 
</TEXT>
