<TEXT>
residents alarmed by pollution are 
demanding the government change policies that helped create an 
economic miracle but also led to environmental disaster 
taipei residents inhale so much dirty air they have almost 
become vacuum cleaners said lin piyao a chemistry professor at 
tunghai university 
blockades of factories protest rallies and marches have become 
ordinary events in taiwan 
demonstrations have forced some businesses to close and others 
to consider moving overseas the government has promised billions 
of dollars will be spent to clean up the mess 
we shall no longer allow certain people to make a fortune by 
having others sacrifice their right to a better environment said 
eugene chien head of the governments environmental protection 
administration 
most of our factories have begun to enforce better pollution 
control but people want to see the results quickly they dont 
trust any commitments 
such comments are new from a government that has gone all out to 
build a prosperous exportoriented economy while doing little to 
force pollution control on industries 
policies that helped take this densely populated island of 20 
million to the rank of 13th in trading volume also made taiwan 
arguably one of the worlds filthiest places 
official reports say 34 percent of the rivers are polluted and 
little clean water is found outside the remote highlands of central 
taiwan 
most villagers have virtually given up protecting the 
rivers which have become drainage ditches for factories said 
shih hsinmin professor of chemical engineering at national taiwan 
university 
a perpetual haze envelops taipei the capital caused by 
pollutants that include exhaust from 1 million cars and motorcycles 
used by the citys 3 million people 
cases of pollution by individual factories have attracted wide 
attention 
chinese petroleum corp a stateowned concern hooked 20000 
nearby residents to a piped water system because their well water 
was so polluted by oil that it became flammable 
a survey by a doctor at national taiwan university hospital 
found symptoms of lead poisoning in half the 64 workers at a 
battery recovery factory in keelung port on the north coast 
thirteen of 32 children at a nearby kindergarten suffered mental 
retardation the doctor attributed to pollution from the plant 
a chorus of protest began in 1987 when the lifting of martial 
law after 38 years made demonstrations legal and allowed greater 
freedom of expression 
many of the 7500 demonstrations held since martial law ended 
have had antipollution themes protesters have conducted hunger 
strikes and dumped dead fish at the doors of government offices 
villagers have held lengthy sitin blockades of several 
factories accused of polluting the environment forcing some plants 
to close and others to pay compensation construction projects have 
been delayed or halted because of the outcry including important 
petrochemical plants and power stations 
taiwans largest conglomerate formosa plastics group responded 
to protests at the proposed site of an ethylene plant by saying it 
might move some manufacturing facilties to mainland china 
officials say they fear hundreds of textile and plastic firms 
that rely on the conglomerates products might follow the 
government has announced plans to clean up staterun factories but 
there is concern that modernizing equipment at the aging plants may 
not help much 
the 10 major staterun companies involved in oil refining 
power generation and steel and fertilizer production have 
announced plans to spened the equivalent of 34 billion on 
pollutioncontrol equipment in the next four years nearly double 
the figure for the previous four 
some private companies have other solutions the china gulf 
plastic corp in miaoli a northern city has provided residents 
with gas masks in case of a large chlorine emission 
environmentalists are not impressed with official efforts to 
clean up 
the government still gives top priority to economic 
development said lin the chemistry professor who also heads 
the taiwan environmental protection union 
critics of the government claim factories rarely are closed for 
violating antipollution laws and are allowed to pay fines instead 
which are much cheaper than buying equipment to reduce pollution 
some environmentalists want the government to phase out 
industries that cause the worst pollution they say it might cause 
a brief economic slowdown but would boost the cleaner 
hightechnology ventures officials view as a key to future 
development 
environmental protection can go hand in hand with economic 
development said shih the national taiwan university professor 
they dont have to contradict each other 
