<TEXT>
now that everybody has played out the 
preliminary roles the wellrehearsed political furor over flag 
burning is headed into reruns the first reprise is in the supreme 
court to be followed depending on the script there by another in 
congress 
everybody includes the flag burners themselves a handful of 
showoffs without whom the whole production would have closed by 
now but that would have been at the cost of a safe showy 
republican campaign issue 
neither side in the political flag parade wavers or burners 
could operate without the other 
the next question to be settled is the constitutionality of a 
law congress passed last fall making it a federal crime to burn 
the american flag the supreme court is going to hear arguments on 
the issue on may 14 in time to make its decision by july 
if that decision matches the ruling that started the whole 
business last june overturning a texas law against flag burning 
congress will make the next move and there is little doubt that it 
will be to approve an amendment to the constitution to ban 
desecration of the flag 
that will take twothirds votes in the house and senate then 
threequarters of the states to ratify the amendment those steps 
would be a foregone conclusion even in the judgment of opponents 
who argue that the first amendment should protect expressions of 
dissent no matter how offensive 
the issue is too incendiary politically for many elected 
officeholders in either party to vote in favor of leaving it 
alone so it has become an argument over how to ban flag burning 
president bush wanted a constitutional amendment in the first 
place saying he doubted there was any other way to ban flag 
burning democratic congressional leaders said it could be done by 
law without constitutional tinkering and they passed one 
including a provision for swift review by the supreme court bush 
let it become law without his signature 
on cue the flag burning types reappeared there being a reason 
for somebody to pay attention to them again they courted arrest by 
burning flags at a federal building in seattle and on the capitol 
steps in washington that provided the test cases they sought and 
federal judges in both cities held the law unconstitutional 
that in turn led straight to the situation bush and the 
republicans had forecast last summer and revived the issue in time 
for the 1990 election campaign 
the interdependence of burners and banners is not the only irony 
in the flag situation the justice department is now making the 
case for a law the administration argued against on grounds that 
it would not pass constitutional muster when it got back to the 
supreme court lawyers for the democratdominated congress are on 
the same side urging the court to uphold the statute 
each side suspects the other of ulterior motives the 
administration sought and got speedy court review some democrats 
suspect that what the republicans are looking for is a decision 
that will overturn the law reviving the issue for another fourth 
of july republicans accused the democrats of trying to get the 
whole thing delayed until fall so that there wouldnt be a 
decision before the november elections 
those suspicions boiled into debate late last month when lawyers 
for the house told the court it should give the case priority in 
the fall term beginning next october republicans protested 
bitterly noting that the law passed last year and asked the court 
to expedite the review to the greatest extent possible 
the democrats insisted that their lawyers had not tried to 
shelve the issue but wanted ample time for full argument and 
consideration because according to rep richard a gephardt the 
majority leader we want the best possible chance of getting the 
court to uphold this statute 
republicans said it was a political dodge you will not 
deceive the american public said rep thomas j bliley jr 
rva they know better and they will remember in november 
the court made those arguments moot when it decided to hear the 
flag cases next month but the house dispute and the three roll 
call votes that ended it show the political power of the flag 
issue 
republicans hoisted a resolution to withdraw the house brief 
that suggested the court case wait until fall and democrats 
deserted their own leaders on what became another series of flag 
votes the final vote was 309 to 101 to order withdrawal of the 
legal brief the democratic leadership had endorsed 
