<TEXT>
the recent turmoil in japans financial markets 
has left its mark on us mutual fund investors 
a tally of the best and worstperforming mutual funds released 
wednesday by lipper analytical services inc said eight of the 10 
biggest losers during the first quarter were invested heavily in 
japanese companies 
the big winners were investments in science and high technology 
several specialty funds also did well 
but overall stock and bond funds posted negative performances 
during the first three months of 1990 according to lipper the 
average total return of general equity funds was a negative 231 
percent following a 121 percent drop the previous quarter 
fixedincome fund performance was a negative 140 percent in the 
first quarter 
by comparison the dow jones industrial average of 30 bluechip 
stocks was down 069 percent and the standard amp poors 500 index 
lost 301 percent in the first quarter assuming reinvestment of 
dividends 
a michael lipper the firms president called the decline 
comforting rather than frightening and said general stock 
funds in particular had far exceeded the typical 10 percent annual 
growth rate of recent years from late 1974 to the end of the first 
quarter these funds grew by an average 165 percent he said 
we take great comfort in that the shortterm declines are 
bringing intermediateterm rates of gain back down to historic 
trends lipper said 
the same may not be true for japanoriented funds which 
historically have produced a number of moneymaking standouts in 
tandem with japans strong economic growth according to the lipper 
