<TEXT>
sales of north americanmade vehicles rose 29 
percent in late march as better sales at general motors corp 
offset declines at ford and chrysler while japanese automakers made 
strong gains 
gms vehicle sales during the period rose 61 percent while 
sales for ford motor co declined 38 percent and chrysler corps 
fell 166 percent 
combined car and truck sales for the nine major us automakers 
rose to a daily average of 43688 in late march compared with an 
average of 42451 during the same period last year the companies 
said wednesday 
car sales were up 27 percent and lighttruck sales rose 32 
percent 
sales in the yearearlier period were relatively soft 
nevertheless gms increase was significant because it followed a 
prolonged period of declining market share said auto analyst scott 
merlis of morgan stanley amp co of new york 
the real story here as we end the first quarter is that a 
new trend has developed and gm is a marketshare gainer he said 
gms share of the domestic car market in late march stood at 
451 percent up from 446 percent during the same period last 
year fords share dropped to 265 percent from 296 percent and 
chrysler tumbled to 97 percent from 13 percent 
gms gains were modest though alongside those made by 
japaneseowned plants in the us the socalled transplants took 
187 percent of the domestic market in late march up from 128 
percent a year earlier 
gms car sales rose 39 percent in late march and much of the 
overall gain came from a 109 percent increase in light truck 
sales including the companys new minivans 
on march 22 gm began offering 1000 rebates on the companys 
trio of new minivans the chevrolet apv pontiac trans sport and 
oldsmobile silhouette gms share of the domestic light truck 
market in late march rose to 405 percent from 377 percent while 
fords and chryslers shares dropped to 338 percent and 203 
percent respectively 
in january chrysler offered a similar rebate on its minivans 
the most popular in the industry and sales soared but since that 
incentive expired jan 31 sales have dropped off 
despite the apparent incentivespurred boost in gms truck 
sales underlying consumer demand appears to be strengthening 
merlis said 
theres some real underlying consumer demand there he said 
if hes right the demand is just beginning to show up car and 
truck sales for all of march and for the first quarter of 1990 are 
lagging behind last years pace 
combined domestic and imported car and truck sales of 1271465 
vehicles last month was 31 percent lower than in march 1989 for 
the first quarter of 1990 sales were 18 percent behind last 
years pace 
drawing firm conclusions about trends in vehicle sales based on 
one 10day reporting period can be misleading since a variety of 
factors including incentives and even weather can affect sales 
but merlis said theres reason to wonder whether the sales 
slump that began in october as the 1990 model year got under way is 
at an end 
if sales can continue at this rate next month that would be 
very encouraging from a consumer standpoint and in terms of a 
general recovery he said 
robert rewey fords vice president for sales took a similar 
view 
we expect the second half of the year to be somewhat 
stronger than the first assuming a pickup in economic growth from 
its present sluggish pace he said 
