<TEXT>
baxter international inc will emerge a stronger 
player in the medical supply business after paring its workforce by 
10 percent and shedding a fifth of its plants according to 
industry analysts 
baxter announced those cuts wednesday as part of a restructuring 
that also includes the sale of several marginal businesses and 
creation of a separate division for diagnostic products part of 
which it may sell to the public 
industry analysts said the costcutting measures were long 
overdue following years of belttightening in the medical industry 
as providers have striven to contain healthcare costs 
hospitals have been pushed up against the wall in terms of the 
cost cuts theyve had to make and thats affecting the suppliers to 
the hospitals as well said jerry fuller of duff amp phelps inc in 
chicago 
analyst joseph francis of smith barney harris upham amp co said 
the austerity measures while unexpectedly severe were very 
positive for baxters future 
what will emerge is a much leaner company in a very 
competitive market francis said this should dramatically 
improve their earnings power 
baxter said that over the next three years it plans to lay off 
about 6400 of its 64300 employees and close or sell 21 of its 
approximately 100 manufacturing plants in 24 countries including 
46 in the united states 
spokesman geoffrey fenton would not identify the plants slated 
for closure but said baxter already has begun to notify those that 
will be affected 
these decisions are in the best longterm interests of all of 
our constituencies chairman vernon r loucks jr said in a 
statement 
baxter must keep evolving to help its customers meet their 
objective of providing highquality health care while controlling 
costs loucks said 
the company also said it planned to raise prices on many 
products and channel more money into research and development 
baxter based in the chicago suburb of deerfield said it would 
post a firstquarter net loss of 375 million to 400 million or 
150 to 160 a share after taking a pretax charge of 566 
million for the restructuring 
the company said the changes will generate annual pretax 
savings of up to 275 million by 1993 and help baxter achieve 
annual growth of 15 to 18 percent in operating income over the next 
several years 
baxter boosted profits by 15 percent last year to 446 million 
on sales of 74 billion 
the companys common stock fell 25 cents wednesday to 2437 a 
share on the new york stock exchange 
fenton said the layoffs included 500 people already cut from the 
corporate headquarters staff 
he declined to identify the manufacturing businesses that baxter 
intends to sell saying arrangements had not been completed he 
said baxter may continue to distribute products of those businesses 
even if it no longer owns them 
baxter said the businesses to be sold had total sales of about 
140 million last year 
the company said it will establish a separate subsidiary for its 
diagnosticsproducts business and is considering selling a minority 
interest in the subsidiary to the public diagnostics accounted for 
14 billion of baxters sales last year 
the company said it was committed to diagnostics products and to 
inhome health care a growing market that baxter latched onto via 
its 1987 acquisition of caremark inc 
caremark was heralded last year for innovation as the sole 
distributor of clozapine a schizophrenia drug that the company 
delivers to patients homes weekly the company also monitors the 
patients for potentially toxic side effects of the drugs 
despite such innovations baxters core business remains the 
manufacture of basic hospital supplies gowns intravenous 
solutions and surgical supplies and the distribution of 
healthcare products manufactured by others said james fenger an 
analyst who follows the company for kemper financial services inc 
baxter said its latest moves were consistent with the strategic 
plan it has been pursuing since it acquired the american hospital 
supply corp in 1985 and caremark 
