<TEXT>
proposed legislation to end the turf battle 
between the federal agencies that oversee stock and futures markets 
would create a single markets and trading commission 
a bill to merge the securities and exchange commission and the 
commodity futures trading commission was introduced wednesday but 
even supporters concede it faces rough going 
meanwhile the chairman of the house subcommittee that oversees 
the sec proposed a bill to curb abuses in the low cost high risk 
penny stock market 
the cftc which regulates the futures exchanges and the sec 
which oversees the securities industry have been squabbling over 
which agency has authority to regulate socalled hybrid 
products such as stock index futures 
the proposed new agency would be phased in over a twoyear 
period and one division would still deal exclusively with physical 
commodities such as metals oil and farm products like wheat pork 
bellies and soybeans 
rep dan glickman dkan who cosponsored the bill with rep 
dennis e eckart dohio said the legislation does not seek to 
create a super sec or a super cftc it is not a takeover of one 
agency by the other 
glickman is a member of the house agriculture committee which 
oversees the cftc and eckart sits on the energy and commerce 
committee that keeps tabs on the sec they said committees in both 
ther senate and house with jurisdiction over each agency would 
retain their oversight authority despite the merger 
congressional oversight has been a stumbling block to previous 
merger efforts and may remain so 
it moves around the furniture and puts them all in one room 
but im not sure if it gets you any benefits said rep glenn 
english dokla chairman of the house subcommittee that oversees 
the cftc 
i think its unnecessary its a kick in the face of the 
commodities industry to suggest that they will lose their identity 
and lose their uniqueness said rep e thomas coleman rmo 
the ranking minority member of the subcommittee 
the cftcsec rivalry heated up after a federal appeals court 
ruled last year that cftc has authority over a financial product 
with any aspect of a futures contract including stock index 
futures 
treasury secretary nicholas brady has proposed stripping the 
cftc of some or all of its authority over financial futures 
and sec chairman richard c breeden has said that at the very 
least the sec should have authority over stock index futures 
glickman and eckart said their bill is a wholesale 
reorganization of how the government oversees these markets 
but a spokesman for the cftc david gary said we see no no 
need to combine the agencies 
the penny stock reform bill proposed by rep edward markey 
dmass would require that all penny stocks be traded through an 
automated quotation system 
penny stocks inexpensive but highly risky securities that 
usually arent listed on stock exchanges are legal but they are 
usually issued by new companies with untested or uneven track 
records 
that makes them risky and often prone to fraud because 
information about their earnings history is hard to come by or 
confirm 
statelevel securities regulators have said penny stock fraud 
costs us investors 2 billion a year 
the proposed legislation would ban blank check stock 
offerings and blind pool penny stocks which offer stock to the 
public in companies that plan to engage in mergers and acquisitions 
but without clearly stating their business goals 
</TEXT>
