<TEXT>
japan must redouble its efforts to meet the 
objectives of a 1986 agreement on increasing the foreign share of 
japans semiconductor market us trade officials said thursday 
were disappointed we think the progress thus far has been 
unsatisfactory a us trade official told reporters under rules 
of the briefing none of the officials may be identified 
the heat is on said another us official were looking 
for results across the board under the original agreement 
with 16 months left before the 1986 bilateral semiconductor 
agreement expires us officials say they want japan to increase 
efforts to help foreign chip producers boost their current 129 
percent share of the market to 20 percent by 1991 the united 
states contends this was agreed to in the pact 
japanese officials have said the 20 percent figure was merely a 
goal 
foreign chips which are mostly american held 86 percent of 
the japanese market at the time of the agreement 
the two countries completed a regular review of the pact 
wednesday 
the officials said most major japanese semiconductor users have 
adopted plans to increase their foreign share of chips a step they 
found encouraging but foreign manufacturers supply only 3 percent 
of the chips used in japanese consumer electronics products and 3 
percent to 5 percent of those used in japanese cars 
by contrast us producers supply 70 percent of the chips used 
in european autos the officials said 
they added that japans ministry of international trade and 
industry is candidly and sincerely working to put the agreement 
into practice 
under the agreement japan also pledged to stop unfair pricing 
of computer chips overseas called dumping us officials say 
japan has kept that promise 
during a regular review of the agreement which is held two or 
three times a year japan told the united states its efforts to buy 
more foreign semiconductors will suffer if washington charges that 
chips face trade barriers in japan under the super 301 clause 
of the us omnibus trade act 
the clause requires us trade officials to prepare an annual 
hit list of trade barriers faced by us products together 
with a deadline for a negotiated resolution aimed at getting the 
barriers eliminated that priority list is due april 30 if 
negotiations fail the united states can impose penalties 
the us government is considering placing semiconductors on the 
list in response to requests from american chip makers the us 
officials confirmed 
us semiconductor industry groups say their limited sales 
success in japan shows that restrictions exist against foreign 
chips while japanese companies have called for us suppliers to 
make greater sales and qualitycontrol efforts 
a japanese official said japanese companies were making serious 
efforts to buy more us semiconductors particularly for 
automobiles and electronic products 
