<TEXT>
the senate agriculture committee voted today 
to substantially change the governments foreign food aid programs 
to better help the worlds hungriest people and encourage emerging 
democracies 
the legislation approved on voice vote would provide food 
grants to the poorest countries reorganize the food aid 
bureaucracy and allow the president more leeway in giving food to 
nations whose governments he wants to bolster 
the bill will be the agricultural trade portion or title of 
the 1990 farm bill that will go the senate floor the house 
agriculture committee has not acted on foreign trade 
this title makes the most dramatic change in american foreign 
food policy in a quarter of a century said committee chairman 
patrick leahy dvt who coauthored the measure with sen richard 
lugar of indiana the panels ranking republican 
ann veneman deputy undersecretary for international affairs and 
commodity programs said the committees staff worked with the bush 
administration to write the bill 
there are areas where we did not agree but nothing so major 
it cant be worked out she said after the committe voted 
the programs provided for in the bill would cost an estimated 
15 billion annually which would be paid directly from the budget 
and by money received from repayment of debts on previous food 
loans the amount is comparable to previous years 
leahy said the bill would make the governments international 
food aid system more reflective of the realities of today 
it also gives the united states powerful new weapons in 
providing critical food aid to emerging democracies in eastern 
europe central america and worldwide he said 
the legislation would establish a food for freedom program 
under which the president could donate food to countries trying to 
set up democracies and spend up to 100 million for agricultural 
necessities such as fertilizers and transportation 
poor countries least able to produce their own food would be 
eligible for food grants and forgiveness of debts incurred through 
previous food loans 
currently food is sold to poor countries at reduced interest 
rates over a 40year term but that only makes a bad debt situation 
worse for those countries leahy and lugar said 
about 12 billion is owed to the united states through 
agricultural programs lugar said we think we have an interest 
in part of that debt and would like in the case of the most 
desperate countries to offer some relief he said 
leahy said the debt forgiveness proposal is aimed at the 
droughtstricken countries of subsaharan africa 
sen chrstopher bond rmo said some parts of latin america 
also should be included in the grant and debt forgiveness plan but 
leahy responded theres only so much debt forgiveness we can do 
countries you are talking about have the ability to raise food 
the legislation makes food grants part of an ongoing policy for 
the first time previously food has been given away on an ad hoc 
basis or in emergencies said an aide to the senate committee 
leahy said the bill also would clean up mismanagement and 
bureaucratic red tape that frustrates the aid programs 
five agencies the agriculture state and treasury departments 
the office of management and budget and the agency for 
international development all now have a say in how food aid is 
distributed 
the bill would put aid in charge of the grant program and make 
usda responsible for the sales program aimed at developing new 
markets 
the agriculture committee accepted an amendment by sen bob 
kerrey dneb requiring the agriculture department to spend at 
least 900 million in fiscal 1991 on the export enhancement program 
and removing the ceiling that has existed on the program 
kerrey said the administration needed the provision to use in 
international trade talks against countries that heavily subsidize 
their own exports to the detriment of the free market 
under the program exporters are given bonuses that bring down 
the cost of us products to foreign countries usda decides which 
countries qualify for those sales 
</TEXT>
