grain and soybean futures prices were mixed in 
early trading today on the chicago board of trade with wheat giving 
up some of the strong gains posted in the three previous sessions 
wheat futures surged wednesday amid fears of a weekend freeze in 
the us winter wheat region and concerns about tight deliverable 
supplies 
the freeze fears have lessened somewhat but tightsupply 
concerns persist following a wall street journal report that 
minneapolis investor irwin jacobs owns about half the wheat 
available for delivery against the may futures contract 
jacobs told the journal he no longer holds any futures contracts 
on wheat and is not trying to squeeze the wheat market 
jerry zusel manager of balfour maclaine corps floor 
operations at the board of trade said wheat traders are more 
worried about the possibility of frost damage to the newly sprouted 
winter wheat crop in the central and southern plains 
stronger export demand supported the corn market while higher 
soybean meal prices helped to boost the beans 
in early trading wheat futures were cent to 1 cents lower 
with may at 369 a bushel corn was 1 cent lower to cent higher 
with may at 268 a bushel oats were cent lower across the 
board with may at 151 a bushel soybeans were unchanged to 1 
cents higher with may at 592 a bushel 
cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mostly 
lower in early trading on the chicago mercantile exchange 
