<TEXT>
eastman kodak co was fined 1 million 
today after pleading guilty to two misdemeanor violations of state 
environmental laws 
kodak was charged with illegally disposing of contaminated soil 
in 1986 and of failing to report a leak of a toxic solvent for five 
days in 1987 
city judge herman j walz accepted the plea agreement but said 
he questioned the wisdom of granting kodak officials and directors 
immunity from prosecution 
the agreement lets people who have participated in criminal 
acts go unpunished walz said it is the opinion of the court 
that corporate officers and employees should also be prosecuted 
kodak was fined 997500 for its illegal handling of the 
contaminated soil assistant attorney general paul mccarthy said 
kodak hired an unauthorized company to haul away nearly 50000 
pounds of soil contaminated with silver 
the incident was one of a series of violations by kodak 
mccarthy said 
kodak was fined the maximum penalty of 2500 for failing to 
report a spill of 5100 gallons of methylene chloride until five 
days after it had been discoveredthe chemical is considered a 
probable human carcinogen by the environmental protection agency 
state officials were expected to announce later today an 
agreement that will require kodak to pay another 1 million to 
settle civil charges brought by the state department of 
environmental conservation 
the rochester democrat and chronicle reported that state 
officials also will announce a legally binding consent order 
requiring independent experts to conduct an environmental audit of 
kodaks chemical operations 
sources familiar with the terms of the order said kodak will pay 
for the study the newspaper reported the sources said the state 
environmental agency will insist the audit be performed by a 
consultant group with no close ties to kodak or the state 
the attorney generals office has been investigating kodaks 
contamination of ground water at its kodak park manufacturing 
facility for nearly two years 
a special grand jury has been looking into kodaks possible 
environmental violations since january it has subpoenaed more than 
80000 documents from the company 
</TEXT>
