<TEXT>
fewer us companies plan to increase their 
capital spending budgets this year compared with 1989 according to 
a national survey released thursday 
dun amp bradstreet corp said 41 percent of the 5000 companies it 
polled plan to spend more on capital projects in 1990 down from 46 
percent that planned bigger budgets last year 
despite the decline dun amp bradstreet economist and chief 
statistician joseph duncan said capital spending remains at 
relatively high levels 
while us firms are less ambitious they continue to increase 
investments to replace plant and equipment he said 
the survey which was conducted in december and january showed 
that 25 percent of the companies planned to cut capital spending 
this year while 35 percent said they would maintain spending at 
1989 levels 
among industries the service sector and the construction 
industry were particularly bullish about increasing spending 
fortyfive percent of the companies in both categories said they 
planned to spend more money this year than last 
larger companies are more likely to increase their capital 
spending annually according to the survey 50 percent of the 
companies with over 10000 employees will spend more while 37 
percent of those with fewer than 500 employees were planning 
increases 
smaller businesses are more sensitive to fluctuations in the 
business cycle particularly with respect to higher interest 
rates duncan said 
the survey was based on a sample of 5000 companies drawn from 
dun amp bradstreets database which includes information on more 
than 9 million us companies and was statistically representative 
of companies of all sizes in all industries 
</TEXT>
