<TEXT>
more than threequarters of chief executive 
officers of us companies contacted in a survey said their 
greatest competitive threat comes from other domestic companies 
not foreign businesses 
about 70 percent of the more than 1100 ceos polled on behalf of 
continental bank of chicago also said their companies 
competitiveness is most strongly influenced by factors within their 
control 
about 51 percent of the executives said us business is at 
least as competitive if not more so with foreign business as it 
was 10 years ago looking ahead seven of 10 ceos said they 
believed us business will maintain or improve its competitive 
position with foreign business over the next 10 years 
about 75 percent of those surveyed believe us companies are as 
good as or better than foreign competition in terms of marketing 
expertise and management quality twothirds said us product 
quality is superior while the american work force was seen as 
stronger than foreign counterparts by 60 percent of executives 
foreign companies were judged better than or equal to us 
businesses only in terms of operating costs by 66 percent of ceos 
and product price by 65 percent 
fewer than onethird of the executives said they believed their 
companies were likely to establish joint marketing or distribution 
agreements with foreign companies within the next five years about 
23 percent already have such agreements 
sixty percent of the ceos said foreign investment in the united 
states has helped improve us competitiveness 
nearly all the executives said a low level of worker training 
and education is the most serious obstacle to building the united 
states competitive strength followed by a shortterm focus on 
earnings by companies 
the survey of 1136 ceos of companies with sales of under 10 
million to more than 5 billion was conducted during 1989s fourth 
quarter by beta research corp of syosset ny the survey has a 
statistical margin of error of plus or minus 135 percentage points 
</TEXT>
