<TEXT>
stock speculators long a shadow force in the tokyo 
stock exchange have been hurt badly by the markets recent heavy 
plunges traders said thursday 
rumors that financially strapped speculators have in turn pushed 
small brokerages close to bankruptcy caused a temporary plunge of 
more than 1000 points thursday in the exchanges chief index 
one broker said more than 30 minor brokerages had been left with 
massive losses 190 million according to news reports by stock 
manipulators who were unable or unwilling to pay for their buy 
orders the broker who refused to be named said his firm had been 
informed of the problem by stock exchange authorities 
traders said the rumor sparked thursday mornings selloff in 
which the 225share nikkei stock average plunge more than 383 
percent from wednesdays close 
exchange officials later denied the bankruptcy rumor in an 
unusual quickly called news conference aided by support from large 
securities and investment trust firms the nikkei rebounded to 
finish the day down 19388 points or 068 percent at 2824906 
speculators in the tokyo stock exchange generally remain behind 
the scenes buying up shares of targeted companies to push up the 
price sometimes with the use of false rumors and then dumping 
them to make profits the number of such investors is unknown 
some of these speculators are believed to have close links with 
gangsters the daily yomiuri newspaper said thursday that japanese 
gangster syndicates have raked in huge profits by investing in 
stocks 
traders said many of the speculators were going broke because 
they had bought stocks using borrowed money repayable at high rates 
of interest 
some speculators have begun using a tactic called teppo or 
gun the placement of false buy orders for their own shares in an 
attempt to get rid of plunging stocks that nobody else wants to 
buy the speculators never intend to pay for the shares dealers 
say 
some securities companies have lost money by buying shares for 
imaginary figures without cash payment said hisao yasuda a 
trader with nikko securities co this could be the end of the 
speculators 
yasumasa shinagawa a trader with yamaichi securities co 
called the nikkeis early plunge thursday a sign that speculator 
groups were collapsing because of financial trouble stemming from 
the markets nearly 27 percent drop so far this year 
at the end of thursdays trading about 24 percent of the 
approximately 1160 issues on the stock exchanges first section 
still had no price quotations indicating that no trades had 
occurred during the day said nikkos yasuda 
he said many of the untraded issues had been manipulated by 
speculator groups 
issues that are the focus of speculators can be easily 
identified by wild price movements unrelated to market trends said 
katsumi nishikido a dealer with nippon kangyo kakuaru securities 
co 
traders say speculators have targeted about 200 issues listed on 
the first section of the exchange about 70 of which are among the 
nikkeis 225 issues 
the price of kagoshima bank shares identified as one such 
issue ended at 860 points thursday down from almost 3000 points 
in early march 
under japanese rules payment for stock orders is not due for 
four days as a result brokerages are vulnerable to losses from 
speculative excesses 
everybody remembers the black monday stock crash they all 
expected the market to rebound like it did then said one broker 
as a result the market rapidly became overbought he said 
ordinarily clients are given thorough initial credit checks 
but followups are rare the broker said 
traders said smaller unlicensed securities firms could go broke 
in the current market because they are more likely to be involved 
with risky investors whereas major securities firms generally 
avoid speculators 
a nomura securities official said major brokerage houses dont 
process buy orders from speculator groups unless they receive cash 
payment 
the big four securities companies nomura yamaichi daiwa 
and nikko are believed to control about 60 percent of the shares 
traded on the tokyo stock exchange 
of 272 securities firms with licenses from the finance ministry 
124 including 22 foreign firms are members of the exchange 
an official in the exchanges investigative arm said the 
issue is basically a problem between securities firms and their 
customers we are trying not to make a big fuss about it if we 
did it might make the market performance even worse 
takaaki okada spokesman for the securities dealers association 
of japan ruled out the possibility of bankruptcies of accredited 
japanese financial institutions because the finance ministry will 
offer to take some actions by the time a company gets into 
trouble 
</TEXT>
