<TEXT>
many in japans financial markets are not expecting 
much help for the falling yen from saturdays meeting in paris of 
the finance chiefs of seven advanced industrial nations 
in the past japans trading partners have worried about a cheap 
yen which makes japanese goods less expensive and more competitive 
abroad contributing to this nations huge trade surpluses 
now japan is concerned that the weaker yen is raising dangers 
of domestic inflation by making its imported fuel and raw materials 
cost more 
but analysts say japans partners in the group of seven are 
likely to do little more than state a general commitment to stable 
exchange rates 
while a lower dollar tends to make us goods more competitive 
against japanese products they add the united states has been 
concentrating recently on other approaches to narrowing its 49 
billion deficit in trade with japan to help fight its own 
inflation dangers they say the united states is happy with a 
strong dollar 
nobody except japan is worried about the weak yen said 
minori takeuchi of chemical bank 
west germany would prefer a strong mark ahead of currency 
union with east germany she added 
in addition to japan the united states and west germany the 
others in the group are britain france italy and canada 
just in case the meeting does decide on action to shore up the 
yen which has fallen about 10 percent this year tokyo market 
players have been reducing their dollar holdings in the last three 
days 
the dollar closed thursday at 15790 yen down more than two yen 
from its closing of 15995 yen on monday its highest in more than 
three years 
market players began to reduce their dollar holdings just in 
case the g7 meeting comes up with something they had not 
predicted although nothing special is expected at the moment 
mamoru tabata a dealer with mitsui taiyo kobe bank said wednesday 
on the other hand there has been speculation that the united 
states was declining to support the yen as part of attempts to 
pressure japan into making concessions in this weeks trade talks 
in washington 
in those talks ms takeuchi said the united states is pressing 
the japanese government to spend more on public works figuring 
that if the government spends more the united states can export 
more here 
japans central bank has been using interest rate increases to 
try to head off inflation and support the yen higher interest 
rates tend to make a nations currency more attractive although 
they also tend to discourage stock investment a problem for japan 
amid a stock market plunge of more than 25 percent so far this year 
in its latest move on march 20 the central bank raised its 
charge for loans to commercial banks by one percentage point to 
525 percent 
citing a possible reason for the group of seven to support the 
yen yoichi itoh chief corporate service officer at sumitomo trust 
and banking said i think the united states might judge that 
higher japanese interest rates might force us interest rates up 
and that some kind of currency stability will be necessary to stop 
japanese interest rates from rising further 
at the end of march the dollar rose 643 yen in nine trading 
days foreign exchange traders said the tokyo market was 
disappointed that japanese finance minister ryutaro hashimotos 
meeting with us treasury nicholas brady on march 23 had produced 
no tangible new measure to support the yen 
at a news briefing on tuesday hashimoto said the dramatic 
changes in europe rather than exchange rates would be the main 
focus of the group of seven meeting he said the meeting was not 
being held to draft policies to deal with the recent instability in 
japanese markets 
at a news conference last week yasushi mieno governor of the 
bank of japan said it was hard to understand why the yen was 
falling when japanese interest rates adjusted for inflation were 
higher than us interest rates and japan still was running large 
trade surpluses 
he suggested that tensions in the soviet union and developments 
in europe were boosting the dollar considered a safe haven 
currency 
