<TEXT>
americans often are accused of having lost the 
yankee love of thrift but the international monetary fund says 
people in some other countries are saving even less notably in 
prosperous northern europe 
it predicted that the trend will continue as the worlds 
population ages older people have less to save for 
the negative trend in national saving rates experienced by all 
the major industrial countries since the early to mid1970s has 
raised serious concerns about the prospects for strong and 
sustainable growth in the world economy said the latest issue of 
the imf survey dated march 19 it appears every two weeks 
the warning is based on a report by a team under bijan b 
aghelvi senior advisor in the funds research department at its 
headquarters in washington 
when people put money into their bank accounts the banks relend 
it to industry for building the factories that will produce more 
goods and jobs in the future if savings are too small industry 
has to borrow from other countries 
governments also save or more often dissave by going 
further into debt when a government spends more than it collects 
in taxes it has to borrow from the savings of its citizens or from 
other countries its taxpayers then have to pay interest on the 
debt 
the united states is a prime example on both counts americans 
of the future will have to pay interest to other countries on the 
billions being borrowed by americans today 
the most recent figures come from the organization for economic 
cooperation and development oecd in paris 
in 1988 the average american household saved only 440 out of 
every 100 left after it paid taxes but americans were not the 
greatest spendthrifts the average swedish household did not save 
at all it drew on past savings or went into debt at the rate of 
360 for every 100 it earned dissavings of 120 per 100 
were also reported from average norwegian families and 140 from 
those in finland 
dutch households saved only 2 of every 100 
of the major industrial countries the japanese were the top 
savers 1520 out of 100 even the thrifty japanese have loosened 
up in 1976 their figure was 2320 
the average west german family saved 1510 of every 100 in 
1975 and only 1260 in 1988 
another study sponsored by the fund warns that a countrys 
capital will be consumed unless money is set aside to replace it 
and more must be put aside as the population grows 
</TEXT>
