<DOCNO> AP900405-0287 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal futures regulators on thursday took 
another step toward regulating groups of traders known as broker 
associations to prevent possible trading abuses like those 
uncovered in chicago last year 
the commodity futures trading commission voted unanimously 50 
to submit for public comment a proposed rule that would provide a 
legal definition of broker associations and require them to 
register with the exchange at which they do business 
broker associations have been loosely defined as formal or 
informal groups of futures traders formed to provide more capital 
to finance trades and more people to handle them 
but the cftcs division of trading and markets concluded in a 
study disclosed last january that broker associations may 
increase the potential for certain types of trading abuses 
the study was an outgrowth of an undercover investigation of 
trading at the chicago board of trade and the chicago mercantile 
exchange the nations two largest futures exchanges which 
resulted in the indictment of more than 40 traders 
only five of the 13 futures exchanges have rules defining broker 
associations and of those only three the chicago mercantile 
exchange the commodity exchange or comex and the coffee sugar amp 
cocoa exchange require broker associations to register 
cftc staffers believe and commission members agreed that 
keeping tabs on broker associations will help them deter abuses in 
the trading pits 
i believe very strongly that we identify and register these 
groups and i also agree that it gives a big assist and augmentation 
to our surveillance program to have this information said 
commissioner kalo a hineman 
in other matters the cftc which oversees the futures markets 
voted to seek public comment on a clarified commission 
interpretation of what types of hybrid financial products are 
exempt from cftc regulations 
hybrids contain elements of both futures contracts and 
securities the interpretation issued last year specifies what 
types of institutions and products are exempt from cftc regulation 
as defined in the cftcs proposed rule broker association 
refers to two or more exchange members who share responsibility 
for executing customer orders profits or losses from trading 
activities or access to each others unfilled customer orders 
the rule would bar participation in the trading activities of a 
broker association unless the association is registered with the 
market or exchange 
interested parties would have 60 days to comment on the proposed 
rule before the cftc takes a final vote on implementing it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

