<DOCNO> AP900405-0289 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
digital equipment corp announced thursday 
it has developed a new process to clean computer circuit boards 
that does not use chemicals believed to damage the earths ozone 
layer 
company officials making the announcement at digitals augusta 
plant where the process was developed said digital is making the 
technology available to other companies as a gesture of digitals 
environmental commitment the maynard massbased company the 
nations secondlargest computer maker after international business 
machines corp 
even before thursdays announcement some companies expressed 
interest in the new process augusta plant manager bob jackson told 
reporters and business representatives 
in the past digital like many computer makers used solvents 
containing chlorofluorocarbons to remove dirt and residues left by 
the manufacturing process from printed circuit boards the debris 
was removed through chemical reactions with the solvent but cfcs 
were released into the air when the solvent evaporated 
digital has developed a process in which minute droplets of 
water are sprayed on the circuit boards from rotating arms a key 
to the technology is a nozzle reducing the size of the droplets 
which are able to clean underneath components 
the circuit boards are washed with a light detergent then 
rinsed twice and blown dry 
the process is exceptionally simple said dana duncan an 
engineering supervisor and one of those who developed the 
technology 
equipment for the process has been installed at digital plants 
in augusta and hong kong and plants in singapore and taiwan are 
being retrofitted said mike hasty a process engineering manager 
who also worked on the technique 
digital is providing information on the new technology through 
the industry cooperative for ozone layer protection a joint 
venture between the federal environmental protection agency and 
industry the venture promotes worldwide reduction of 
chlorofluorocarbons 
digital said it has been working on the cfcreducing process for 
two years 
reduction of cfcs which are also used in refrigeration foam 
blowing and aerosols will aid in efforts to counter global 
warming known as the greenhouse effect scientists say cfcs 
are believed to break down the protective ozone layer surrounding 
the earth 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

