<DOCNO> AP900405-0297 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the house energy and commerce committee 
overwhelmingly approved a farranging air pollution control bill 
late thursday after resolving a dispute on how to deal with midwest 
concerns over acid rain controls 
the measure now goes to the house floor where it is likely to 
come up for debate early next month 
the committee cleared the legislation by a vote of 421 rep 
william e dannemeyer rcalif was the sole dissenter 
rep john dingell dmich the committee chairman called the 
bill significantly better in protecting the environment than a 
version approved by the senate earlier in the week 
the committee moved swiftly to approve the legislation after 
giving the nod to a compromise agreement aimed at easing concerns 
from midwest congressmen over the high cost of acid rain controls 
the acid rain compromise worked out during three days of 
closeddoor negotiations among committee members and staff was 
approved by a 394 vote erasing the last major roadblock to 
committee passage of the bill 
the process has been rather curious said dingell alluding 
to the lengthy private negotiations that eased the committee 
through several obstacles 
we have negotiated rather than fought and it has worked 
he said 
the lopsided committee vote following senate approval of its own 
clean air bill by an 8911 margin earlier in the week put clean air 
legislation on track for congressional approval this year 
both bills call for sweeping emission controls on factories 
automobiles and electric power plants by the end of the decade the 
bush administration has estimated the senate legislation would cost 
215 billion to the economy yearly when all provisions go into 
effect the house bill has been said to be slightly cheaper 
house speaker tom foley dwash had indicated that he wanted 
to begin floor action on the legislation in early may final 
legislation would have to be worked out in a conference committee 
because of differences between the house and senate bills 
this legislation is long overdue its a real victory for 
our lakes lungs and resources said rep gerry sikorski dminn 
the acid rain issue had dominated the three days of closeddoor 
bargaining among members of dingells committee as members and 
staff worked under a deadline to try to complete action on the 
entire bill before congress departs for its easter recess friday 
earlier the committee had reached a consensus on provisions 
dealing with curbing urban smog and controlling toxic industrial 
releases 
a lot of blood was spilled in these debates said rep jim 
cooper dtenn who vigorously opposed a cost sharing provision to 
help the midwest 
but the compromise received coopers support as well as that of 
all but four of the committee members all from texas reps ralph 
hall and john bryan both democrats and jack fields and joe 
barton both republicans 
as a way to help midwest states pay for cleaning up dirty 
utility plants the measure included a pollution allowance 
system and a 1year extension for initial compliance under some 
circumstances 
it allows us to recoup some costs said rep michael oxley 
rohio 
nevertheless oxley said this is a tough tough bill for my 
part of the country and were going to feel it for a long time 
critics of the measure have said it would cause electric rates to 
jump 
more than 150 lobbyists representing everything from 
environmental groups to the steel industry gathered outside the 
house hearing room were the negotiations were being held awaiting 
word of an agreement 
the clean air legislation is aimed at imposing steep pollution 
controls on a broad range of industry automobiles and coalfired 
electric power plants to curb emissions of acid rain smog and 
toxic chemicals 
earlier in the day the environmental protection agency released 
a new annual report that showed as had previous reports that 
federal air pollution laws are failing to ensure healthy air in 
more than 100 cities across the country 
according to the epa survey which reported results on six 
pollutants during 1988 more than 121 million people lived in areas 
where the air did not meet federal health standards 
the epa assessment said the urban smog problem became 15 percent 
worse in 1988 compared with the year before in part because of an 
exceedingly hot summer and levels of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen 
dioxide increased slightly 
levels of carbon dioxide and dust or dirt declined somewhat 
the emissions are largely the product of automobile travel 
industrial releases or the burning of fossil fuels by electric 
power plants 
the report shows the magnitude of the air pollution problem 
still remaining said epa administrator william k reilly adding 
that it reinforces the need for new tougher air pollution controls 
the senates approval of a clean air bill tuesday was the first 
time either the house or senate has passed tighter air pollution 
legislation since 1977 
emotional regional disputes have blocked progress on a bill for 
years usually because of the high cost of reducing sulfur dioxide 
emissions from power plants 
while most members of congress as well as the bush 
administration agree on a required 10 million ton reduction in 
annual sulfur dioxide emissions to curb acid rain the dispute has 
focused on how much of a burden should be carried by the midwest 
where some of the dirtiest plants are located 
</TEXT>
